<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 00:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Empire State Games end with the Western region atop the medal count </HEADLINE>
By JOHN KEKIS
<TEXT>
<P>
   BINGHAMTON, N.Y. (AP) - An exhausted Fred Smith leaned back in
his chair at Binghamton University and sighed his annual sigh.
</P>
<P>
   ''The games are over and we already have this melancholy
feeling,'' Smith, director of the Empire State Games, said Sunday,
only a few hours after the four days of Olympic-style competition
in 28 sports had ended. ''Binghamton has really raised the bar. The
enthusiasm here was incredible, almost unprecedented.''
</P>
<P>
   It marked the first time that Broome County had hosted the
games, and local officials made it clear they want to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ''We look forward to the opportunity,'' Binghamton Mayor Richard
Bucci said. ''We want it back more so than ever. At the end of this
event we're just as enthused about it as we were a year ago. We'd
take them back next year if that were a possibility without any
reservation.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not likely to happen for at least three years. The 2001
Empire State Games will be next July 25-29 in the Utica-Rome area
before returning to their original home in Syracuse for the 25th
anniversary.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said Ithaca, Rochester, Buffalo and Albany already have
submitted letters or called inquiring about hosting future games
after that, and Bucci said he would, too.
</P>
<P>
   About the only drawback here was that the swimming venue was 40
miles away in Cortland. That didn't allow competitors there to
sample one of the games' nicest features, mingling with the other
athletes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're going to work real hard next year to make sure we
address these issues,'' Smith said. ''We'll have our work cut out
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith said the basic blueprint for 2001 was in place and the
venues, which will be spread out considerably, will be solidified
in November.
</P>
<P>
   ''We'll make it work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said sports like Tai Kwon Do and women's lacrosse might be
added for 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The final medal counts by region ended like this: Western led
with 89 golds and 252 total; Central had 218 medals, 54 of them
gold; Long Island had 191, including 67 gold; Adirondack had 165,
including 50 gold; Hudson Valley had 158, including 52 gold; and
New York City had 154, including 70 gold.
</P>
<P>
   During competition, 97 records were set, all but 11 of them by
Masters competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Heather Fiore didn't set any marks, but she did win her first
gold medal after eight failures.
</P>
<P>
   Fiore, the all-time leading scorer at Canisius College and now
women's coach at Johnstown High School, scored 16 points and
Melanie Halker of Watervliet had 21 as Adirondack defeated New York
City 103-95 on Sunday in the open women's championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is awesome!'' said Fiore, whose 3-pointer with 7:04
remaining gave Adirondack a 75-67 lead. ''This one was tough. I've
been out of school for three years. Getting back into shape was
challenging. I don't have time to run and do all those things.''
</P>
<P>
   ''She finally got one,'' Adirondack coach Theresa Wenzel said.
''It had to do with teamwork and pure desire.''
</P>
<P>
   Maureen Holohan added 18 points, Mary McKissack had 12, and
Jolene Johnston 10 for Adirondack.
</P>
<P>
   Fiore, who did not play for Adirondack when it won gold in 1997,
said it didn't take long to realize that this team was different
from the other eight she had played on.
</P>
<P>
   ''From the first day of practice, this team came in and worked
as hard as it could,'' said Fiore, whose basketball low point was
losing the state championship on her home court at Queensbury High
School in 1992. ''Everybody got along very well. We worked
together. I don't know if I've ever been on a team where we've
worked that hard together. We knew that it was a special team, that
it was going to be tough to beat us.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, New York City made it difficult, building an early lead
behind the hot shooting of Cindy Johnson, who scored 19 of her
game-high 28 points in the opening period.
</P>
<P>
   Antoinette Saitta had 18 points, Carolyn Harvey had 17, and
Kimberly MacMillan 12 for New York.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-pointer by Catrina Washington with 2:29 left in the first
half put New York up 42-34, but two baskets in the final minute by
former Siena star Cori Drummond made it 42-40 at the break.
</P>
<P>
   ''We went in at halftime and said, 'You've worked too hard to
let it slip away. Stop playing scared and start playing like a team
instead of individuals,' '' Wenzel said. ''And that's what they
did.''
</P>
<P>
   The game was tied four times in the second half before
Adirondack went on an eight-point run. A lay-in by Drummond gave
Adirondack a 70-63 lead midway through the period and New York was
unable to rally.
</P>
<P>
   ''The second half we really picked up our defense,'' said
Halker, who also starred for Siena in college. ''She (Johnson) was
ready to win the game. In the first half, it was hard stopping her.
But in the second half, we focused on her more.''
</P>
<P>
   Two free throws by Fiore, who missed only one of 12 foul shots,
gave Adirondack an 84-74 lead with 4:38 remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ''We couldn't get it together,'' said Johnson, who plays college
ball for Delaware. ''We fell apart with the offense. We weren't
running the plays the way we were in the first half, and I think it
fell apart a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   Adirondack hit 13 free throws in a row in the final three
minutes to secure the victory, its second win over New York in as
many days. Adirondack won Saturday night 105-93.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think we enjoyed playing that team again,'' Fiore
said. ''It's hard to play teams back-to-back, especially playing
them at eight at night and then coming back and playing them at
noon. We knew what they did, but they knew us, too. It came down to
who had the legs at the end of the game. Everybody was pretty
tired, but when you want something as badly as we wanted it you
don't think about being tired anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   For Fiore, the elation of winning might have to last a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't know if I'll play next year. This could be my last
one,'' she said. ''This was my goal and I got it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
