<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ukrainians Complete OpSail Journey  </HEADLINE>
By ANN S. KIM
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTLAND, Maine (AP) -- It isn't the tallest of tall ships, the
oldest, or the prettiest. And its journey in this summer's
international parade of tall ships has been far from smooth
sailing.
</P>
<P>
   But a Ukrainian ship that struggled to reach the OpSail 2000
finish line in Portland Harbor after about three months at sea has
also won the hearts of many Americans as the little ship that
could.
</P>
<P>
   The Bat'kivshchyna, sailing with no government funding, ran
aground and sustained damage days into its journey. Its radio gave
out in the Atlantic, leaving the U.S. Coast Guard unsure of its
whereabouts. And it missed OpSail's first stop in Puerto Rico
because of a navigational error.
</P>
<P>
   Dymtro Biriukovich, the vessel's 63-year-old captain, took the
miscues in stride during his 8,000-mile journey.
</P>
<P>
   ''Of course, we had some small problems,'' said Biriukovich.
''But it is normal because it is a long trip.''
</P>
<P>
   Once it reached U.S. shores, the Bat'kivshchyna (pronounced
bat-keev-SHIN'-a) attracted its own following. Admirers brought
gifts -- food, beer, cigarettes, fuel and equipment -- to help the
ship continue its journey. In Portland, the crew was feted with a
feast of Maine lobster Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Americans have sort of adopted the ship as their
sweetheart of all of the ships,'' said Roy Kellogg, the captain's
son-in-law. ''They love the underdog.''
</P>
<P>
   Biriukovich, who holds a doctorate degree in civil engineering,
spent about 2&AMP;frac12; years building the ship out of an old trawler. He
coated the hull in cement, added two collapsible masts, fixed the
deck and installed the cabin. Completed in 1991, the trawler was
reborn as a 90-foot gaff-rigged schooner named Bat'kivshchyna, or
''Fatherland.''
</P>
<P>
   The OpSail trip -- its first venture beyond Mediterranean waters
-- began in April. Within a week, the Bat'kivshchyna hit rock bottom
in the Dnieper River, leaving a 3-foot gash in the hull and
destroying a toilet.
</P>
<P>
   Storms in the Mediterranean then ripped the mainsail, and the
ship had to stop so the crew could sew it up.
</P>
<P>
   ''They were bobbing around and that's when they got seasick,''
Kellogg said. ''It took them two days, because everybody was
getting seasick. They could do it for about 15 minutes at a time
before vomiting.''
</P>
<P>
   The satellite phone went out near Gibraltar, cutting off the
steady stream of e-mail messages the ship had been sending ashore.
It turned out the phone company was sold and the Bat'kivshchyna's
service was dropped.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-May the Bat'kivshchyna's radio had died. The Coast Guard
sent out broadcasts asking other ships to be on the lookout and
considered launching a search as far back as Africa.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg and his wife, Katya, were waiting in San Juan, Puerto
Rico, the site of the first OpSail stop. They heard no word about
the Bat'kivshchyna until a Danish sailboat passed along a confused
message that indicated the ship was bypassing San Juan and heading
to Norfolk, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Kellogg later learned that the ship's global positioning system
-- bought for about $100 in Ukraine -- was giving false readings and
that the Bat'kivshchyna ended up farther north than intended. The
crew navigated to Virginia with a sextant and compass and arrived
early for the festivities there.
</P>
<P>
   ''It seemed sort of like something my father-in-law would do.
'Oh we missed it,''' Kellogg said.
</P>
<P>
   In Portland this weekend, tens of thousands of people waited for
hours to tour some of the world's largest tall ships, Argentina's
Libertad, Brazil's Cisne Branco, and the U.S. Coast Guard's Eagle.
</P>
<P>
   But the smaller Bat'kivshchyna did not go unnoticed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We didn't realize how many Ukrainians were in Maine,'' said
Steve Femiak, the founder of Connecticut Friends of Ukraine
Expedition. ''They're all just happy to be on a boat from the
homeland and to see the flag.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the old friends made themselves at home below deck,
while first-time visitors perused information about Ukraine. The
crew hawked souvenirs -- flasks with Russian insignias, refrigerator
magnets shaped like musical instruments, fake fur hats -- to help
pay for the trip.
</P>
<P>
   The OpSail voyage is just the beginning for Biriukovich's
seaworn ship. He wants to sail around the world -- albeit slowly --
to teach people about his country. Next year, he wants to sail the
Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's my dream,'' he said. ''Let us step by step inform
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Discover Ukraine Expedition: http://www.discover-ukraine.kiev.ua
</P>
<P>
   OpSail Maine: http://www.opsailmaine.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
