<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sports, Politics Converge in Philly  </HEADLINE>
By TED ANTHONY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- You pass the people, and you hear the
platitudes: phrases like ''giving 110 percent'' and ''the back
nine'' and ''the home stretch'' and ''came to play.'' And why not?
This is a pro-sports complex, after all.
</P>
<P>
   But these words aren't coming from the usual suspects -- the
sundry Flyers and Phillies and 76ers who usually haunt arena row at
the rump of South Philly. This time around, they're coming from
handlers and delegates, politicians and press secretaries.
</P>
<P>
   Let's face it: The walls, precarious for years, have fallen.
Sports is politics, politics is entertainment, and a building that
began the year as a sports arena for cheering, victory-rabid fans
is, for a week, the country's premier political arena for cheering,
victory-rabid partisans.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the Super Bowl of American politics,'' says Leslie
Goodman, the GOP convention's chief spokeswoman. ''This,'' she
says, ''is our Greatest Show on Earth.''
</P>
<P>
   A telling comparison for an entertainment epoch. And it can veer
into the decidedly bizarre: On Wednesday night, House Speaker
Dennis Hastert, R-Ill., will open the evening's session with the
help of none other than The Rock, the glowering
athlete-slash-entertainer who cracks skulls and threatens inferiors
each week for the World Wrestling Federation.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm just wondering if The Rock is going to get up there and
say, 'Finally! The Rock! Has come back! To Philadelphia!''' jokes
Ike Richman, the PR guy for Comcast Spectacor, which operates First
Union Center, the convention venue.
</P>
<P>
   Used to be that politicians appreciated actors and athletes but
didn't necessarily emulate them -- or become them. But then came
Ronald Reagan, a one-man vessel of acting (''Bedtime for Bonzo''),
sports (''Win one for the Gipper'') and savvy politics (''It's
morning in America''). The NBA's Bill Bradley and baseball's Jim
Bunning went to Congress, and by the 1990s cross-pollination was
here to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Then, quickly: The creator of ''Designing Women'' got tight with
the Clintons. Michael Jordan made ''Space Jam.'' Shaquille O'Neal
cut a CD. Former Clinton press secretary Dee Dee Myers started
doing scripts for ''The West Wing.'' Garth Brooks practiced with
the San Diego Padres. Nebraska's football coach is running for the
House of Representatives.
</P>
<P>
   And this week, Bob Dole, erstwhile GOP presidential candidate,
will be a convention correspondent for -- get this -- Comedy Central.
</P>
<P>
   So what better site for a political production? A convention
center seems so button-down, a big hotel so corporate and beige.
Why not the home of major-market sports teams, the place celebrity
and money and forward-moving, easily understood narratives call
home?
</P>
<P>
   ''It's the perfect place,'' says John Dizikes, a professor at
the University of California-Santa Cruz who studies the places that
sports and politics occupy in American culture.
</P>
<P>
   ''Politics is far more entertainment than it used to be,'' he
says. ''The conventional political types, the political
establishment, are not willing to accept that they've entered into
a different cultural period.''
</P>
<P>
   At the First Union Center, nearly all the visible Flyers and
76ers trappings, from basketball hoops to backup hockey sticks to
actual staffers, have been moved out -- many to the nearby
Philadelphia Naval Shipyard. There are Republicans in Flyers head
coach Craig Ramsay's office, Republicans in the locker room,
Republicans in the team whirlpool room and laundry facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The arena's operators, walking Sunday afternoon through what was
recently a hockey rink and is now a floor for state delegates, see
many similarities between athletic and political spectacles.
</P>
<P>
   ''Oklahoma's about at center ice,'' says Peter Luukko, president
of Comcast Spectacor Ventures.
</P>
<P>
   ''Delaware's about where the backboard is,'' Richman volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goalie's in Arkansas,'' Luukko shoots back.
</P>
<P>
   He elaborates. ''Sports, entertainment and politics are meshing.
They're all becoming one. Everything is designed to totally
entertain people instantly.''
</P>
<P>
   Spectacor officials are trying to learn from the unique amalgam
of political fanfare and entertainment that the Republicans have
brought to town.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's consensus-building,'' Luukko says. ''We've got to make
people feel like they're in charge, but make sure they do the right
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   He laughs. ''I guess we've become politicians.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
