<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philadelphia Has Solid GOP Past  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE FEINSILBER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Strange thing about the Republicans meeting
here in Philadelphia. You'd think they'd brag about this city's
solidly Republican past. Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   When every other big city in America was voting Democratic, and
many were in the hands of Democratic machines and bosses,
Philadelphia was in the hands of a Republican machine. In the dark
Depression, Philadelphians even supported Republican Herbert Hoover
over Democrat Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   From Lincoln through FDR, the Democrats were a fringe party
locally, on the outside looking in. The dominant Republicans
themselves were divided between blue-blood old aristocracy
reformers and the GOP bosses. The bosses generally prevailed.
</P>
<P>
   Republican Philadelphia stood for everything that made
Republican blood boil elsewhere: bloated contracts. Votes bought
with booze. Dead people voting. Ward politics. The spoils system.
If you wanted a job as a cop, or you wanted a zoning variance, or
you wanted to fix a ticket, you went to your Republican ward
leader.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when national Republicans stood for civil service
reform and temperance and were unwelcoming toward immigration,
Philadelphia Republicans stayed in power through patronage, whiskey
and finding jobs for immigrants, says local historian Kyle Farley.
</P>
<P>
   Farley and Christopher Klemek are Ph.D. candidates in history at
the University of Pennsylvania, earning their way through school by
giving history tours of their city. This week they are showing off
the city's GOP roots to visiting Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   They point to Philadelphia's massive City Hall as a testament to
the city's old ways. When it was under construction, it was
intended as the tallest building in the country, but Republican
contractors kept winning lucrative contracts to add on to it.
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years passed before it was finished in 1901, and by that
time other buildings elsewhere were taller. But it was big, and it
provided a lot of jobs to just-off-the-boat immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia was the despair of reformers everywhere. The city,
wrote Lincoln Steffens, the famed turn-of-the-century muckraker,
was ''corrupted beyond redemption.'' Not merely corrupt, but
content to be so.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe because Philadelphia was so good to Republicans, the GOP
liked to meet here. This week's is the sixth Republican convention
since the newly minted party first assembled in Musical Fund Hall
in 1856 and nominated John Fremont on an anti-slavery platform. He
lost.
</P>
<P>
   Civil War hero Ulysses S. Grant was successfully nominated for a
second term in the Academy of Music, the nation's oldest grand
opera house, and the Republicans came up with a third winner here
with William McKinley, president from 1897 to 1901.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans returned to Philadelphia twice in the 20th
century to award their nomination to Wendell Wilkie in 1940 and
Thomas E. Dewey in 1948. Both came up losers.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, corruption finally drove the Republicans out after
World War II. Democratic reformers Joseph Clark and Richardson
Dilworth campaigned against the machine and took over City Hall.
The Republicans elected their last mayor, Barney Samuel, in 1948.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 0101 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000731.0012 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hundres Protest Dr. Laura Show  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOLDEN VALLEY, Minn. (AP) -- About 300 people rallied outside
KARE-TV studios to protest the station's decision to air Dr. Laura
Schlessinger's upcoming television show.
</P>
<P>
   The protesters Sunday vowed to boycott businesses that advertise
during the Paramount-syndicated show, which will begin airing on
KARE Sept. 11.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights activists have criticized the radio talk-show host
for her views on homosexuality, which she has called ''deviant''
and a ''biological error.''
</P>
<P>
   ''This sort of message, which is about so many things, but in
particular about homophobia, continues to foster the kind of
behavior that allows hate crimes,'' said Tom Kane, a member of the
Episcopal Diocese of Minnesota's Department of Outreach and
Advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   KARE officials said the station purchased the show for its fall
lineup before learning about Schlessinger's controversial views.
But they said the station will honor its contract.
</P>
<P>
   ''Silencing voices of any kind prior to seeing even a single
frame of tape, raises a whole other set of potentially harmful
issues regarding freedom of expression,'' KARE general manager John
Remes said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 0104 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000731.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Boomer Battle May Not Draw Boomers  </HEADLINE>
By GENARO C. ARMAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The first election between two presidential
candidates of their own generation may not be enough to get
millions of baby boomers to the voting booths and reverse a decline
in turnout that began in the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Census Bureau projections released Monday show that the number
of Americans ages 45 to 64 increased from 54.3 million in 1996 to
61.9 million this year, a 14 percent jump. Baby boomers are
generally classified as those born between 1946 and 1964, meaning
the oldest ''boomers'' will be 54 this year.
</P>
<P>
   Typically, older Americans are more likely to vote than their
younger counterparts, Census analyst Jennifer Day said.
</P>
<P>
   ''People who vote usually own their own home, are older, and
have a higher level of education,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the baby boomers, many of whom protested the Vietnam War and
grew jaded by the Watergate scandal in their youth, may not rush to
the booths this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Neither of these are exciting candidates,'' said G. Terry
Madonna, political science professor at Millersville University in
Millersville, Pa. ''A lot of voters believe they are looking at two
sides of the same coin without any big differences.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first time, both major parties will feature candidates
from the baby boom generation: Texas Gov. George W. Bush (age 54),
the presumptive Republican nominee, and his Democratic counterpart,
Vice President Al Gore (52).
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Gans, director of the Washington-based Committee for the
Study of the American Electorate, said the candidates are trying to
overcome ''a turnoff of the political enterprise.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It will take a long time to reverse'' declining voter turnout
rates, Gans said.
</P>
<P>
   Turnout for the 1996 presidential election dipped to 48.9
percent, a record low according to Census data dating back to 1930.
Turnout was 55.1 percent in 1992, and 62.8 percent in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, 32.7 percent of the voting-age population cast ballots
in the midterm congressional elections, down 4 percent from four
years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   While it's early to forecast what turnout will be in November,
Gans said he wouldn't be surprised to see turnout dip even lower.
</P>
<P>
   ''The real question is do people care,'' Madonna said. ''Is the
interest sufficient to have turnout hold its own?''
</P>
<P>
   By November, the number of Americans eligible to vote will be
about 206 million, 9 million more than in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While the 45-64 age group increased 14 percent from 1996, there
also was an 8 percent increase in the 18-24 age group, signifying
the maturation of baby boomers' children.
</P>
<P>
   ''But typically, those kids don't vote,'' Day said.
</P>
<P>
   Ted Jelen, a political science professor at the University of
Nevada at Las Vegas, says the correlation between age and voting is
not based on how old people are, but on ''when they were young.''
</P>
<P>
   The very oldest age group, those 65 and older who lived through
World War II, tend to be more active in civics. ''You find high
turnout with them throughout the years,'' Jelen said.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect to see a big spike in turnout thanks to the
aging baby boomers, he added. ''Their formative experiences will
affect that.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Census Bureau: http://www.census.gov/
</P>
<P>
   Committee for the Study of the American Electorate:
http://www.gspm.org/csae/
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
