<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Group Spotlights Philly Homeless  </HEADLINE>
By TODD SPANGLER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Yolonda Johnson-Young has a tarp roof over
her head, an old couch to relax on and a cot to sleep on at night.
The kids are slurping up Fruit Loops and looking around at the
weed- and gravel-covered lot they call home for now.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome, Johnson-Young says, to Bushville.
</P>
<P>
   That's the name activists have given their encampment on a plot
ringed with trash and broken bottles in North Philadelphia, an
abandoned property that the Kensington Welfare Rights Union and its
leader, Cheri Honkala, selected as base camp for protests designed
to bring attention to the impoverished during the Republican
National Convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it helps,'' said Johnson-Young, a market researcher
who has lived in a shelter for more than a year. ''The issue is
very serious here in Philadelphia and we have groups from all
across the country here trying to make the same point.''
</P>
<P>
   The point, the urban campers say, is affordable housing, better
wages and health care -- more help for the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   Bushville's 150 or so tenants include students from
Massachusetts and Maine, homeless from Rhode Island and a women's
group from Little Rock, Ark. Their tents and tarpaulins pitched,
they talk about subjects as disparate as civil disobedience and
child care and plan for a Monday march through the city.
</P>
<P>
   People line up for milk and corn flakes. Flies buzz the lot. The
rules include no drugs or alcohol, and shirts and shoes must always
be worn.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're trying to win the American public,'' says Willie
Baptist, who is with the welfare rights union. We're not just here
for self-expression.''
</P>
<P>
   In Philadelphia, where police are allowed to ticket people
living or lying on city streets, the plight of the impoverished has
been brought to a head, not only by the convention, but also by the
recent fatal shooting of a homeless man by Amtrak police.
</P>
<P>
   City police have said no homeless are moved unless problems
arise and that policy would remain in effect during the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Baptist contends, however, that police have moved the homeless
off the streets over time.
</P>
<P>
   Other activists see it differently.
</P>
<P>
   Sister Mary Scullion, who runs Project HOME -- which houses
hundreds of homeless and provides jobs and education services --
said $5.6 million in city funding has helped reduce the number of
homeless on the streets.
</P>
<P>
   In a yearly census of homeless in Philadelphia, Project HOME
counted 220 people. Last summer, the number was more than 470,
Scullion said.
</P>
<P>
   She estimated that Philadelphia has about 20,000 people who
experience homelessness each year, but the vast majority of those
go to a shelter or find a program to enter.
</P>
<P>
   ''People think about the person on a grate, but homelessness
mostly affects women and children you don't even see,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 0109 </TRAILER>
