<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congressmen Get Private Philly Party  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN SOLOMON
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- They flew over the Philadelphia skyline in a
helicopter owned by an aerospace contractor. Their kids took a dive
in a pool hastily built for free by union workers.
</P>
<P>
   They jumped in the cockpit of a Commanche helicopter flight
simulator, stood near a Scud missile and peeked inside the Marine's
latest aircraft -- the troubled MV-22 Osprey.
</P>
<P>
   Life's not so bad for members of Congress at the Republican
convention who are ''roughing it'' in some old Navy row houses near
the convention center.
</P>
<P>
   The ''Congressional Village,'' as it is being called, is
temporary home to 75 GOP congressmen this week in Philadelphia.
It's the product of a novel merger of political money, Pentagon
goodwill and a congressional need.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is great,'' said Rep. Rick Hill, R-Mont., as he whizzed
by on a scooter. Hill was one of the congressman who took up the
opportunity to have a close, secure location near the convention
center.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Curt Weldon, R-Pa., a senior member of the House Armed
Services Committee, came up with the idea to convert a closed Navy
base on the grounds of the Philadelphia Naval Shipyard into a
mini-entertainment capital.
</P>
<P>
   And special interests, including many major defense contractors
with business before Weldon's committee, came through with $100,000
in cash and donated services to complete the job.
</P>
<P>
   There were free hot-air balloon rides, antique cars to drive,
live elephants, a parade of 300 fire trucks, a swimming pool
quickly erected by union workers who donated their time, free
helicopter rides donated by contractor Augusta Aerospace and a tent
full of food and drink provided by Metro Machine, a defense
contractor at the adjacent Naval shipbuilding yard.
</P>
<P>
   Among those to attend: California Reps. Mary Bono and Randy
''Duke'' Cunningham, Missouri Rep. Jo Anne Emerson, New York Rep.
Amo Houghton and Nebraska Rep. Lee Terry, who sat smiling on the
steps of his row house Sunday with his wife and newborn baby.
</P>
<P>
   But it isn't just for fun. ''This is all about building
relationships. This is a long-term investment,'' said Charles
Pizzi, an official with the Chamber of Commerce, which helped
underwrite the effort, including a party Sunday night.
</P>
<P>
   Others to chip in included local Philadelphia businesses and
major defense contractors such as Litton Industries, Lockheed
Martin, Boeing and Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Weldon is hosting his own fund-raiser, complete with
entertainment from the Mummers, a famous hometown band that marches
in the city's New Year's parade, and rock guitarist Stump Baxter of
the Doobie Brothers rock group.
</P>
<P>
   The congressman will raise a couple hundred thousand dollars for
his political action committee, CURTPAC, which he will use this
fall to try to help Republicans keep control of Congress, aides
said.
</P>
<P>
   And on Tuesday, another congressman key to military contractors,
Rep. Jerry Lewis of California, will be honored on the grounds with
a party and ''tribal feast'' with the theme of the summer TV hit
''Survivor.'' Lewis is chairman of the House Appropriations
subcommittee that controls defense spending.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing, which is helping underwrite Weldon's fund-raiser, got an
added bonus when the Pentagon agreed to ship more than 40 pieces of
its hardware to the site for congressmen to tour hands-on.
</P>
<P>
   One of those to make it -- the much-maligned MV-22 Osprey, the
Marine's newest aircraft that operates both like a helicopter and
airplane but which has had some high-profile crashes.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it is important to support the process,'' said Boeing
Vice President Roger Krone, standing just a few feet from Weldon.
He noted his company will donate to the Democratic convention next
month in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Boeing executives and military officials get
the chance to bend congressmen's ear about business and try to
allay any concerns about the Osprey. ''The people who fly it feel
it's safe,'' Navy Lt. Commander Mike Dunn said.
</P>
<P>
   Weldon makes no apologies for calling on special interests to
help pay for the makeshift accommodations for members of Congress,
noting he openly identified the contributors. He added a bipartisan
flavor by bringing Democratic congressmen and the city's Democratic
mayor to the site.
</P>
<P>
   But he acknowledges the event will help defense contractors,
including those who chipped in, and the Pentagon, which took the
rare step of moving its wares for display at the site.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't get members to go to military bases,'' Weldon said.
''I want them to see this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 0110 </TRAILER>
