<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel's Knesset To Vote on Barak  </HEADLINE>
By RON KAMPEAS
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM (AP) -- Two parliament votes taking place on the same
day could be the key to reversing Prime Minister Ehud Barak's
political fortunes, teetering on the brink of disaster since he
agreed to attend the Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
   The Knesset on Monday was to determine Israel's next president
and also vote on a no-confidence motion brought by opponents of the
peace process.
</P>
<P>
   Barak commands the loyalty of only 42 Knesset members. But
another 20 or so in the opposition in the 120-member unicameral
chamber have said they would not topple his government over peace
moves.
</P>
<P>
   Barak's candidate for president was a better bet. Shimon Peres,
a former prime minister who was an architect of the first interim
peace accord with the Palestinians, was favored to win the largely
ceremonial role.
</P>
<P>
   The votes come on the last day of the Knesset's summer session,
and if Barak's minority government survives the no-confidence
motion -- as it is likely to -- Barak will be free to pursue his
peace agenda unhampered by parliamentary maneuvers until October.
</P>
<P>
   That would allow Barak time to build up support for far-reaching
concessions to the Palestinians proposed at Camp David, especially
on giving them some control over East Jerusalem. Barak's readiness
to go to Camp David, Md., lost him the support of three hawkish
coalition partners and plunged him into a minority government.
</P>
<P>
   Channel Two said Peres was far ahead of the only other
contender, Moshe Katsav of the hard-line opposition Likud party.
Peres can count on 58 legislators, while Katsav has 40 backers.
</P>
<P>
   That left 22 legislators belonging to two ultra-Orthodox parties
holding the swing vote. The ultra-Orthodox have identified more
with the Likud's foreign policy in recent years, and many see the
54-year-old Katsav -- who himself is religiously observant -- as the
more sympathetic candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Peres also has advantages among the ultra-Orthodox, and has
only to win three of their votes to secure the presidency. When he
was prime minister, his governments were consistently generous to
this chronically impoverished sector of Israel's society; in
addition, Peres' wife, Sonya, is herself Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, Katsav's Likud party infuriated the ultra-Orthodox
last month when it opposed a bill that would enshrine into law
exemptions from the military draft for religious seminarians. At
the time, some ultra-Orthodox leader openly said Katsav had lost
the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Peres would be an asset to Barak's peace agenda. Precisely
because the presidency is seen as above politics, presidential
pronouncements on matters of state carry considerable weight. In
1982, President Yitzhak Navon's hinted opposition to Israel's
Lebanon invasion was decisive in reversing support for that war.
</P>
<P>
   Peres' predecessor, Ezer Weizman, openly backed Barak's peace
initiatives, and helped earn them popular support. Weizman was
forced to resign this month after a police report concluded he may
have committed fraud and breach of trust, although it did not
recommend prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Katsav has tried to turn his resume as a gray, second-tier
minister -- he held the transport portfolio -- into an advantage,
saying he would be less ''political'' and more unifying than Barak.
''We don't need a second prime minister, we don't need a second
foreign minister,'' has been his motto.
</P>
<P>
   In public opinion polls, Peres is by far the more popular
candidate. Controversial as prime minister -- a job he assumed from
1984-86 and from 1995-96 -- the 76-year-old Nobel laureate has
assumed the mantle of elder statesman since losing the 1996
elections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
