<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White Sox 11, Angels 7, 10 Innings  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN NADEL
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. (AP) -- Jeff Abbott and Carlos Lee hit two-run
singles in the 10th inning Sunday night as the Chicago White Sox
rallied for an 11-7 victory over the Anaheim Angels.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox scored two runs in the eighth, three in the ninth
and four in the 10th in winning for just the fourth time in 11
games.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas and Magglio Ordonez opened the 10th with singles
off Al Levine (2-4), the fifth Angels pitcher, and Herbert Perry
sacrificed but reached on a fielder's choice to load the bases with
nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott and Lee followed with their hits to give the White Sox a
four-run lead and knock out Levine.
</P>
<P>
   Winner Keith Foulke (2-0), the fifth Chicago pitcher, got the
final five outs for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's Garret Anderson hit a sacrifice fly off Foulke with
one out and the bases loaded in the ninth to tie the game 7-7. Troy
Glaus then lined to third, sending the game into extra innings.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox took a 7-6 lead in the top of the inning off
Angels closer Troy Percival on a two-out, two-run double by Mark
Johnson and an RBI double by Ray Durham.
</P>
<P>
   Durham's hit was his first in six at-bats, and just Chicago's
third in 17 at-bats with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   The blown save was the eighth for Percival, who preserved 6-5
Anaheim victories the previous two days for his 24th and 25th
saves.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels took a 6-2 lead by scoring three runs in the seventh
on pinch-hitter Orlando Palmeiro's suicide squeeze bunt and a
two-out, two-run triple by Tim Salmon.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox scored two unearned runs in the eighth on a
two-out error by third baseman Glaus, the fourth of five Anaheim
miscues, and a check-swing double by Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   Mo Vaughn, mired in a 1-for-20 slump, blooped a two-out, RBI
double off Jim Parque in the fifth to give the Angels a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jose Valentin hit a solo homer in the first off Seth Etherton,
his 17th, and Chris Singleton added an RBI double in the second to
make it 2-0.
</P>
<P>
   Bengie Molina's sacrifice fly in Anaheim's half of the second
and a solo homer by Benji Gil in the third, his second in two days
and fifth of the season, tied the game 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   Parque allowed eight hits and five earned runs in 6 1-3 innings.
Etherton gave up nine hits and two runs in 6 2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Before the game, the Angels acquired outfielder Ron Gant from
the Philadelphia Phillies for pitcher Kent Bottenfield, the winning
pitcher in Anaheim's victory Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox acquired catcher Charles Johnson and designated
hitter Harold Baines from Baltimore for catcher Brook Fordyce and
three minor league pitchers Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
Notes: Etherton and Parque, opposing each other in the big leagues
for the first time, were crosstown rivals in college. Etherton
(USC) beat Parque (UCLA) in their two head-to-head meetings. Glaus,
then UCLA's third baseman, homered in both games. ... Darin Erstad,
who has a big league-leading 170 hits and a .372 batting average,
hit a first-inning single to snap an 0-for-10 dry spell. He also
singled in the fifth and seventh innings, giving 56 multiple-hit
games -- tops in the majors. ... Anaheim starters combined for a
10.07 ERA in the team's previous eight games, allowing 44 runs on
75 hits in 39 1-3 innings. ... Johnson and Baines are expected to
be in uniform Tuesday night when the White Sox play at Texas.
Chicago is idle Monday. ... Gant is expected to report to the
Angels in time for Monday night's game against Detroit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 0123 </TRAILER>
