<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Sounds Lofty Themes  </HEADLINE>
By TOM RAUM
<TEXT>
<P>
   CINCINNATI (AP) -- George W. Bush is leaving the partisan attacks
to others as he makes his way to the Republican National
Convention, courting voters in the battleground state of Ohio with
a pledge to ''set our spirits high.''
</P>
<P>
   No Republican has won the White House without winning the
Buckeye State, and independents wield heavy influence in
presidential elections. ''The last two elections we haven't done so
well, but that's going to change come November,'' he told a
rain-soaked rally Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Slowly making his way to the convention, Bush is spending two
days in Ohio, which carries 21 electoral votes. He had rallies
planned Monday in Dayton and Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   On the eve of the convention, Bush reached out for bipartisan
support.
</P>
<P>
   ''My job is to lift the spirit of the country,'' Bush said
Sunday. ''My job is to set our spirits high. My job is to say a
united nation can achieve that which we want: to make sure people
are not left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Since leaving Austin, Texas, on Friday, Bush has been traveling
through states that voted for Clinton in the last two elections but
which GOP strategists hope to capture in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   He and wife Laura went to church Sunday and worked on their
convention speeches. Mrs. Bush addresses the convention Monday
night, during its first prime-time session.
</P>
<P>
   Between his wife's speech and one by retired Gen. Colin Powell,
Bush will make a live video presentation to convention delegates
from a school in Columbus.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Bush had campaign stops scheduled in Charleston,
W.Va., and Harrisburg, Pa. He planned to arrive in Philadelphia,
the convention city, Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Besides making one reference to ''my opponent'' Sunday during
his pitch for saving Social Security, Bush left the partisan
fireworks to others.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whoever would have thought you would see Microsoft split up
and the Clintons still together?'' said Rep. Steve Chabot, the
second impeachment prosecutor to stump with Bush on his tour to the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cunningham, a local radio talk show host, compared Bush's
White House bid to Ronald Reagan's 1980 win against Democrat Jimmy
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's elect another governor from the West to scour out the
White House of filth and degradation. God bless America!''
</P>
<P>
   Scott McClellan, Bush campaign spokesman, said the speakers were
''expressing their own opinions'' and that they were not
necessarily shared by Bush. ''The governor is focusing on his
agenda,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, President Clinton won Ohio, 47 percent to Bob Dole's 41
percent; 11 percent of the voters here picked Reform Party
candidate Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Four years earlier, Clinton took 42 percent to President Bush's
38 percent, while Perot received 21 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the keys to winning is reaching out to independents and
ticket-splitters,'' said Bush spokesman Ari Fleischer. ''That's one
of the reasons why Ohio is so important to Governor Bush -- it's
home to so many independent voters.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's appearance Sunday was delayed by 15 minutes while medics
tended to Helen L. Geiger, 73, of Cincinnati, who collapsed at the
rally and was rushed to Bethesda North Hospital where she was
pronounced dead, Blue Ash firefighters said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 0129 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000731.0028 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Misses GOP Convention  </HEADLINE>
By WILL LESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- For the first time in 32 years, Pat Buchanan
is not attending the Republican National Convention. He plans to
head to the beach in Delaware for ''some writing and thinking'' --
maybe even watching a little convention coverage on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Establishment Republicans seemed relieved, though some
conservatives say the absence of Buchanan, a Reform Party
presidential candidate, leaves a void.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois said if there's much nostalgia for
Buchanan at the convention, ''I haven't seen it.''
</P>
<P>
   ''When he left the Republican Party, he marginalized himself,''
said Hyde. ''I wish he would return to journalism and give up his
quest for the Holy Grail.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan doesn't expect too many surprises at the GOP
convention, which he says will be scripted ''like the Academy
Awards.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's sort of a Muzak convention,'' Buchanan said in an
interview with The Associated Press. ''The ones we went to were
rock 'n roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan has been to conventions as a young aide to Richard
Nixon, an aide to Ronald Reagan, a conservative commentator and for
the last two conventions as a feisty challenger for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Some conservatives said they will miss him.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's really sad,'' said Buchanan enthusiast Sharon Kray of
Athena, Ore. ''He added a sparkle to the convention.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan said conventions should have some surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ''My old belief is that conventions are a place where people and
parties come together to argue over ideas and issues and agendas,''
he said. ''That is the kind of politics I love, the passion of
ideas and conflict.
</P>
<P>
   ''But it's their party now. It's who they are and what they want
to be.''
</P>
<P>
   When he failed to gain traction against well-heeled opponents
like Steve Forbes and George W. Bush, the likely nominee, Buchanan
switched to the Reform Party and is involved in a power struggle to
remain on its ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Those in the most conservative wing of the GOP acknowledge
Buchanan's absence gave Bush the freedom to mold this convention in
a centrist image.
</P>
<P>
   ''They have to be happy he isn't here,'' conservative activist
Paul Weyrich said. ''He was red meat for the conservative
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's most memorable moment at the Republican National
Convention came in 1992 when he gave a fiery speech on opening
night.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what conventions are all about,'' said Phyllis
Schlafly, a veteran conservative activist and president of the
Republican National Coalition for Life. ''Where are the exciting
speakers? We need some excitement in the Republican Party.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're going to have quite a few nobodies as speakers, plain
people,'' she said, referring to plans to have a diverse set of
ordinary Americans speak at the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's 1992 speech drew a clear line about the division
between conservatives and their opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a religious war going on in our country for the soul
of America,'' he told the cheering crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats immediately jumped on the reference to ''a religious
war'' and some Republicans later said the speech hurt President
Bush's re-election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, Buchanan wasn't given a prominent role at the
convention that nominated Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our people were treated horribly,'' Buchanan said. ''When you
walk into a convention with 200 delegates and 3 million votes, you
should be treated as part of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Many here say the 2000 convention -- and the Republican Party --
is not about Pat Buchanan any more.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan is ''not in the equation,'' said Andrea Sheldon
Laffery, executive director of the Traditional Values Coalition, a
group representing evangelical interests. ''The issue here is
George W. Bush and the Clinton-Gore record.''
</P>
<P>
   Her father, the Rev. Lou Sheldon, said GOP sentiment for
Buchanan has about disappeared.
</P>
<P>
   ''The reason that Pat Buchanan is fading is that a greater than
Buchanan has arisen,'' he said, referring to the joy conservatives
felt when Bush named conservative Dick Cheney to the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Some say Buchanan's presence would be good for Bush in the fall
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Buchanan were here, there would be creative tension,''
Weyrich said. ''The Bush people would be worried about what he
would say or do.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like firebrand politics. This is dull.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 0132 </TRAILER>
