<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Family Warms the Stage  </HEADLINE>
By KALPANA SRINIVASAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Slow to embrace the political spotlight,
Laura Bush will move to center stage Monday to symbolically open
the Republican National Convention for her husband, Texas Gov.
George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The prime-time address will bring the reserved former librarian
front and center before an audience of millions, and serve as the
bookend to Bush's closing speech Thursday, when he accepts his
party's presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Her remarks will focus on literacy, an issue central to her
private life as a teacher and which she has championed from the
governor's mansion.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush's pivotal role in launching the four-day convention
reflects her own journey, even as she accompanied Bush down a
winding political path.
</P>
<P>
   When they married in 1977, Bush promised that she would never
have to make a political speech. Then, in no time flat, Bush
mounted a losing bid for Congress and his wife was called on to
address the crowds.
</P>
<P>
   He often jokes that it's the only political promise he ever
broke.
</P>
<P>
   Campaigning in Sunday in Ohio, Bush proudly noted his wife's
presence.
</P>
<P>
   ''Guess who's kicking off the convention tomorrow?'' he teased.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's two gubernatorial campaigns and his presidential bid each
drew a cautious response from his wife, who feared exposing herself
and their twin daughters -- now age 18 and college-bound around
Labor Day -- to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was the last person on board,'' she told The Associated
Press earlier this year about her husband's White House bid.
</P>
<P>
   But she has increasingly stepped out on her own, giving
interviews and stumping on her own for her husband.
</P>
<P>
   As first lady of Texas, her causes have mirrored her interests.
She has coordinated an annual book festival to help Texas authors
and raise money for libraries. She has said she will continue those
pursuits if her husband wins.
</P>
<P>
   Later this week, Mrs. Bush will be feted at a luncheon by the
Federation of American Women where, in a twist, the Texas governor
will be one of the featured speakers on behalf of his wife.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bush is not the only relative taking up the mantle here
until Bush arrives here at the convention on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A brother, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush, will be ''very actively
engaged as a surrogate speaker,'' said convention Chairman Andrew
Card.
</P>
<P>
   And Jeb's son, George P. Bush, plans to be visible this week.
His string of convention-related appearances ends with a floor
speech Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
   Though not fully bilingual -- his mother Columba is Mexican --
George P. said his speech would ''be peppered with phrases in
Spanish.''
</P>
<P>
   The 24-year-old is viewed as a lightning rod to help attract
young and Hispanic voters. On Sunday, he greeted youth activists
painting signs for the gathering and attended a clean-up project in
a park across from the convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''I consider myself a minor player in the whole process,'' the
younger Bush said. He said he's using the opportunity ''to add a
personal touch to politics,'' by touring the country on behalf of
his uncle.
</P>
<P>
   His prominence in the campaign is in marked contrast to Bush's
twin daughters, Jenna and Barbara, who have kept a low profile
throughout.
</P>
<P>
   They ''will not have much of a public schedule during the
convention,'' Card said, although they will be on hand for each of
their parents' speeches.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's other siblings also expected to attend the convention.
</P>
<P>
   Doro, his sister and wife of a Washington lobbyist, plans to
help ''energize the delegates and volunteers,'' Bush spokesman Ray
Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Brothers Neil, a business consultant, and Marvin, a venture
capitalist, are expected to be part of a pool of activists who will
speak daily to state delegations, according to Card, the convention
chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Former President Bush will be saluted Tuesday night during a
tribute to past GOP presidents, but is unlikely to make any formal
remarks. He and former first lady Barbara Bush are expected to
avoid the spotlight this week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 0141 </TRAILER>
