<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> GOP Platform Light on Attack  </HEADLINE>
By CALVIN WOODWARD
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Republicans ratify a statement of policy
principles Monday oddly lacking in that staple of political
discourse -- attacks on the other guy.
</P>
<P>
   In contrast to a Democratic platform cast in the tradition of
slamming the opposition while tooting your own horn, the Republican
one toots and toots.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Republicans mentioned President Clinton 153
times in their platform, seeming to spend as much time going after
him as promoting their own candidate.
</P>
<P>
   In the new GOP platform, Al Gore is named twice. And that was by
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   Word went out to platform writers: Keep Clinton and Gore out.
Make it about what candidate George W. Bush and his Republicans
have in mind.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was a very conscious decision,'' said Ginny Wolfe, speaking
for the Republican National Committee on the eve of the party's
convention. ''This is a document that is about what we want to do
with the future. It's not about the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats did not hesitate to take on Bush by name in the
document they approved in Cleveland on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Their platform is suffused with criticism of Republicans in
general, and major policy areas have something biting about Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, they link him with the Republican whose name they most
like to use, a former House speaker gone from politics but not
forgotten.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Bush tax slash ... is bigger than any cut Newt Gingrich
ever dreamed of,'' the Democratic platform says. ''It would let the
richest one per cent of Americans afford a new sports car and
middle class Americans afford a warm soda.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic platform does not measure up to the
Republican one of 1996 when it comes to being preoccupied with the
other side.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans that year introduced Clinton in their own preamble
and went on to call him things like ''master of excuse and
evasion'' and attack ''Clintoncare'' -- his old health care plan.
</P>
<P>
   They slammed ''Bill Clinton's tax bill of 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   This year's platform refers only to the no-name ''largest tax
hike in history in 1993.''
</P>
<P>
   Criticism is made here and there of the ''current''
administration.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates on the GOP platform committee sometimes struggled for
words that would make the point about supposed Democratic sins
without naming the sinners.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know we don't want to say 'Clinton-Gore,''' delegate Ellen
Williams of Kentucky mused as she reviewed a draft.
</P>
<P>
   The platform that delegates settled on during the weekend
showcases Bush's centrist-sounding agenda while yielding to social
conservatives on the abortion and family issues they care about
most.
</P>
<P>
   But habit dies hard and the effort to ignore the Democratic
presidential candidate and the president fell just a bit short.
</P>
<P>
   In rushed language on defense, there's an errant slap at Clinton
for a ''kowtow'' to China. Gore is mentioned twice in a critical
reference to his security agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The words made it past a subcommittee and the full platform
committee even as GOP officials boasted about the fruits of the
party's forward-looking, self-defining and Gore-free labors.
</P>
<P>
   Unless they can find a last-minute way to reopen a done
document, the wayward language will remain.
</P>
<P>
   ''If there is some limit to candidate Gore's new agenda for
America as global social worker,'' the passage concludes, ''he has
yet to define it.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   EDITOR'S NOTE-- John Affleck in Cleveland contributed to this
story.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: 1996 GOP platform:
http://www.rnc.org/2000/platformTOC
</P>
<P>
   1996 Democratic platform:
http://www.democrats.org/hq/resources/platform/index.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 0142 </TRAILER>
