<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Tries To Woo Young Voters  </HEADLINE>
By MATT KELLEY
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- James Cortez is just the kind of voter John
McCain is trying to bring to the Republican Party -- young, Hispanic
and enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Cortez, 21, got the Arizona' senator's autograph
after traveling from San Diego to the Republican convention with a
group of other young Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   He says McCain appealed to his generation in part by comparing
himself to Luke Skywalker -- hero of the original ''Star Wars''
films.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought it was the coolest thing!'' Cortez said. ''It said,
'Hey, I'm not above you, I'm on your level.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain is trying to get other young Americans to think that
voting Republican is the coolest thing. He planned to speak Monday
to MTV correspondent John Norris at the Hard Rock Cafe. And he was
to join Oklahoma Rep. J.C. Watts to talk up plans for a bus tour to
campaign for congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   McCain often says that fighting the cynicism and lack of
political participation of young people is one of his main goals,
and one reason he has worked hard to cut the influence of money in
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''Many Americans, particularly the young, can't see beyond the
veil of cynicism and indifference,'' McCain said Sunday in a speech
to a ''shadow convention'' organized by political reform activists.
''They can't imagine themselves as part of a cause greater than
their self-interest.''
</P>
<P>
   That cause, McCain now says, should include electing Texas Gov.
George W. Bush president. McCain on Sunday asked the delegates he
won in last winter's primaries to vote for Bush, saying the nation
doesn't like ''sore losers.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I need every one of you to give this campaign the same amount
of enthusiasm and participation you did for our primary campaign,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The delegates groaned when he said he was releasing them to
Bush, and several said they would not support the Texan.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think I can vote in good conscience for Bush. I think
he's sending the wrong message,'' said James Manning, a McCain
delegate from New York.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, loudly cheered, told his delegates, ''You have our
eternal gratitude.'' He choked up with emotion, his eyes
glistening, as he thanked his political supporters for ''a good
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain won about 240 convention delegates before ending his
campaign under the weight of Bush's bigger victories in March. Much
of McCain's support had come from moderate Republicans,
independents and ticket-switching Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   About 70 of his delegates had been replaced by Bush loyalists,
and many among the 170 or so he had left had said they would fall
in line behind the victor.
</P>
<P>
   ''John McCain is a great candidate,'' said Connecticut delegate
Benjamin Davol. ''But George Bush is our standard bearer and it is
time to rally behind our nominee and get going.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 0142 </TRAILER>
