<HEADLINE> Corrupt Chinese Official Sentenced  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN LEICESTER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- China sentenced a senior official to death Monday
for bribery in a high-level prosecution aimed at reducing public
anger over corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng Kejie and his mistress amassed nearly $5 million in
bribes, the largest amount ever divulged by the government. He
would be the most senior official executed in a yearslong campaign
against corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng, 66, a former deputy chairman of the national legislature,
was convicted of accepting the bribes while he headed a poor
southern province, the official Xinhua News Agency said in
announcing his sentence by the No. 1 Intermediate People's Court in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng has 10 days to appeal but Xinhua did not say if he would
do so.
</P>
<P>
   Pervasive graft and a string of large corruption and smuggling
scandals involving government, police and army officials have badly
damaged public acceptance of the communist party's half-century in
power.
</P>
<P>
   To restore their image, Chinese leaders have announced a series
of punishments against senior officials, breaking with the party's
traditional penchant for secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Party investigators found that Cheng took kickbacks to approve
building projects, promotions and commodity deals, plotting with
his mistress to amass a fortune for their future marriage.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng was expelled from the party and dismissed as vice chairman
of the national legislature in April. A party spokesman blamed his
downfall on the ''temptations of women and money.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheng's ill-gotten gains far surpasses the $850,000 in illegal
earnings for which a deputy provincial governor was put to death in
March, the highest-ranked corrupt official executed to date.
</P>
<P>
   Many Chinese and party functionaries believe Beijing is really
using the anti-corruption campaign to settle scores with officials
now in disfavor.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng's case is said to have tainted Li Peng, the party's No. 2
leader and head of the national legislature. Cheng was caught in a
widening investigation into smuggling, kickbacks and other
corruption in Guangxi, a poor southern region whose rugged coast is
a haven for smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng, a member of China's Zhuang ethnic minority, headed
Guangxi's government from 1990-98 and was its deputy Communist
Party secretary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 0144 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000731.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Activists Gather on Convention Eve  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER BROWN
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Police say they are willing to ''bend over
backward'' to accommodate peaceful protests around the Republican
convention, but demonstrators say they are willing to go to jail
for their cause.
</P>
<P>
   A homeless march, which did not receive a city permit, was
planned at midday Monday, and both police and protesters expect it
to feature arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizer Cheri Honkala, director of the Kensington
Welfare Rights Union, said up to 5,000 people will march to the
First Union Center where they plan a large-scale civil
disobedience.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got this one moment in time to demonstrate to people in
this country and around the world that this is how serious we are
about raising these issues of homelessness and poverty in this
city. People are willing to go to jail to raise those issues,''
Honkala said.
</P>
<P>
   Protests this weekend were mostly peaceful with little need for
police action.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're willing to bend over backward, only to a point though,''
police commissioner John Timoney said. ''What can you do when they
say, 'We're taking to the streets? We're going to march, we're
going to disrupt the convention.' Well, that's not going to
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, a festival atmosphere prevailed at the Unity 2000 rally,
which police say drew up to 5,000 people. Protesters listened to
musicians and inspirational speakers, as they marched and danced
through downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Police reported few incidents and no arrests. So far, the
rallies have lacked the confrontation of the protests last fall in
Seattle at the World Trade Organization meetings, which featured
about 50,000 people and resulted in millions of dollars in property
damage.
</P>
<P>
   ''Today was about showing solidarity in a peaceful way, showing
we can live the message we are preaching,'' said Margaret Richards,
a member of the Philadelphia Gay and Lesbian Task Force.
</P>
<P>
   After Sunday's parade, protesters held an afternoon rally near
the Philadelphia Museum of Art and listened to speakers including
AFL-CIO President John Sweeney and National Organization of Women
Executive Director Patricia Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   The few confrontations over the weekend illustrated police's
willingness to allow protesters leeway.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not going to push things to a confrontation unless we
have to,'' said Capt. William Fisher, who got into a shouting match
with an abortion rights activist Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Face flushed red, Fisher stood chest to chest with the protester
and told him that the group's permit only covered a block down the
street. But after the argument, about 30 police who had clustered
across the street backed down, allowing the protesters to remain.
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said the weekend freebies would not continue
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's Sunday, we're in a very forgiving mood. We're not going
to be as forgiving in Monday morning traffic,'' Timoney said.
</P>
<P>
   Some protesters said conflicts with police this week were
inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   ''We just concentrate on doing what we have to do to get our
message out,'' said David Cartney, 19, who marched with 11 other
self-proclaimed anarchists Sunday. ''The police are going to arrest
whoever they want to arrest and beat up whoever they want to beat
up.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On The Net: Kensington Welfare Rights Union --
http://www.kwru.org
</P>
<P>
   Protest organizing site -- http://www.r2kphilly.org/
</P>
</TEXT>
