<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 01:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cheney Reconsiders Congress Votes  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Dick Cheney is defending his voting record
amid attacks from Democrats, saying his votes for ''the policies of
Ronald Reagan'' were among his best achievements in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But George Bush's pick for vice president acknowledged that as
times have changed so have his views and he'd probably support
funding for Head Start and vote for the Equal Rights Amendment --
things he opposed back in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Greeted by a cheering crowd of several hundred supporters upon
his arrival at the Republican National Convention, Cheney played up
his experience as both a seasoned Washington insider and corporate
executive who has ''been out in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   He wasted no time taking on the issue of his voting record in a
short speech, underscoring how GOP-friendly it was. He didn't
mention votes against a resolution to free Nelson Mandela and a ban
on ''cop-killer'' bullets -- all under attack by Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''One of the things I feel best about ... is my record voting
for smaller government, lower taxes ... the policies of Ronald
Reagan,'' said Cheney, whose wife, Lynne, and daughter, Mary,
accompanied him to the rally.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney, a former House member from Wyoming who was secretary of
defense in the Bush administration, was scheduled to attend a
breakfast honoring Wyoming Gov. Jim Geringer on Monday. He also
planned to attend convention sessions and work on his acceptance
speech, aides said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats are focusing on Cheney's votes against the school
lunch program, Head Start and the Clean Air Act in TV ads that
started airing in 17 battleground states Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ''What does Cheney's record say about their plans?'' the ad
asks. ''What are their plans for working families?''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday talk shows, Cheney said, ''I might find a couple I
would do differently'' if he had to vote on the same issues today.
</P>
<P>
   He said he would support funding for Head Start, consider a ban
on cop killer bullets and support the Equal Rights Amendment with
modifications.
</P>
<P>
   He defended his vote on Mandela, saying his political party was
viewed as a terrorist organization that has ''mellowed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign issued a point-by-point rebuttal of the ad,
saying Cheney did support a bill that increased funding for Head
Start in 1982 and opposed other bills because he thought it was
more important to deal with the government's huge budget deficit.
</P>
<P>
   While he spoke proudly of his 25 years as a Washington insider,
Cheney attempted to distance himself from the political arena in
Washington and praised states for being at the root of the nation's
economic success.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you get out there and look back at Washington, you
frequently end up scratching your head,'' said Cheney, who will
leave his post as chief executive officer of the oil services firm
Halliburton Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney said he and Bush would unite the Republican Party and
''reach out across the aisle'' to conservative Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what we're trying to do ...'' he said, stumbling on the
year, ''with the 19, excuse me, the 2000 campaign -- that's right,
it's the 21st century.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
