<HEADLINE> American League Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Brook Fordyce hustled the whole way.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Traded late Saturday night while the Chicago White Sox were in
California, he rushed across the country to Baltimore. He joined
the Orioles just in time Sunday to get two hits and score twice in
a 10-7 win over Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, several teams might be in a hurry to make deals. The
deadline for making trades without waivers is 4 p.m. EDT.
</P>
<P>
   ''I didn't even get a chance to thank Brook for what he's done
here,'' White Sox manager Jerry Manuel said. ''We hate to lose him,
he's been a big part of the energy and chemistry here.''
</P>
<P>
   Told Fordyce had contributed to a victory, Manuel said: ''They
won. Way to go, Brook.''
</P>
<P>
   In other AL games, Chicago outlasted Anaheim 11-7 in 10 innings,
Detroit edged Texas 8-7, Oakland beat Boston 5-2, Seattle topped
Toronto 10-6, New York downed Minnesota 7-4, and Tampa Bay beat
Kansas City 7-6 in 10 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Orioles got Fordyce and three minor league pitchers from the
AL Central leaders for catcher Charles Johnson and designated
hitter Harold Baines.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Mora, traded to Baltimore from the New York Mets in a
package for Mike Bordick on Friday, added an RBI single.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Luis Matos drove in four runs and stole four bases, tying
the Orioles' record set by Brady Anderson. John Parrish (1-1)
earned his first major league victory.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is one of them games where I just got by. The guys really
did a great job behind me,'' Parrish said.
</P>
<P>
   David Segui, in his second game with Cleveland after being
traded by Texas, hit his fifth career grand slam.
White Sox 11, Angels 7, 10 innings:
</P>
<P>
   At Anaheim, Jeff Abbott and Carlos Lee hit two-run singles in
the 10th for Chicago, which scored two runs in the eighth and three
in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas and Magglio Ordonez opened the 10th with singles
off Al Levine (2-4), and Herbert Perry sacrificed but reached on a
fielder's choice to load the bases with nobody out.
</P>
<P>
   Abbott and Lee followed with their hits to give the White Sox a
four-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Foulke (2-0) got the final five outs for the victory.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's Garret Anderson hit a sacrifice fly off Foulke with
one out and the bases loaded in the ninth to tie it 7-7.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox took a 7-6 lead in the top of the inning off
Angels closer Troy Percival on a two-out, two-run double by Mark
Johnson and an RBI double by Ray Durham.
Tigers 8, Rangers 7:
</P>
<P>
   Dean Palmer hit a two-run homer and an RBI single in the first
two innings as Detroit built a big early lead at The Ballpark in
Arlington and held on.
</P>
<P>
   The Tigers scored six runs in the first inning for the second
straight night. Juan Gonzalez had an RBI single, Palmer hit his
20th homer and Shane Halter had a three-run triple.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, traded by the Rangers to the Tigers in the offseason,
was 3-for-5 and finished 8-for-16 in his only trip to Arlington
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Willie Blair (8-2) went five-plus innings, giving up four runs
on seven hits and three walks.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Jones got three outs for his league-leading 29th save in 30
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Texas starter Darren Oliver (2-6) lasted only two innings,
allowing seven runs on eight hits.
Athletics 5, Red Sox 2:
</P>
<P>
   Rolando Arrojo lost in his Boston debut as Sal Fasano homered
twice and drove in a career-high five runs at Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Arrojo was 5-9 with a 6.04 ERA with Colorado before being sent
to the Red Sox in a seven-player trade Thursday. He lost his fifth
straight decision, walking the bases loaded in the second inning
and setting up Fasano's first career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   Fasano added a solo homer in the seventh.
Mariners 10, Blue Jays 6:
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson drew a team record-tying five walks, scored two
runs and stole two bases as Seattle beat Toronto at Safeco Field.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Rodriguez and Jay Buhner homered for the Mariners, who won
despite being outhit 10-5. Seattle is 6-1 against the Blue Jays
this year, outscoring them 71-42.	   Henderson matched the club mark for walks
shared by Rodriguez
and Tino Martinez. Henderson has 2,031 career walks and moved
closer to the record of 2,056 held by Babe Ruth.
Yankees 7, Twins 4:
</P>
<P>
   Tino Martinez and Paul O'Neill each drove in three runs and New
York won at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   The AL East leaders returned home after a 5-2 road trip.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill, who once angrily kicked a ball back to the infield
while with Cincinnati, made another blooper-like play in the sixth
inning. After fielding a single in right field, he wound up to make
a throw -- only to have the ball slip out of his hand and roll
behind him.
Devil Rays 7, Royals 6, 10 innings:
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Williams capped a big series by hitting an RBI single in
the 10th inning that gave Tampa Bay a four-game sweep.
</P>
<P>
   Williams also homered as the Devil Rays won their fifth in a
row. He drove in eight runs in the series.
</P>
