<HEADLINE> Stocks Rise in Early Trading  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rose in early trading Monday as investors
gravitated back toward some of the technology shares that were
pummeled last week.
</P>
<P>
   But, the markets remained shaky after some disappointing
earnings reports and signals that the economy is still robust -- a
situation that might cause the Federal Reserve to interest rates
again.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 6.05 at 10,519.41 in the
first half-hour of trading. It lost nearly 75 points Friday and was
down 2 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq was up 32.75 to 3,695.75 Monday after dropping more
than 10 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index was up 6.50 to 1,426.48.
</P>
<P>
   To get a better idea of where the economy and inflation stand,
investors this week will be closely be watching reports on consumer
spending, new home sales, manufacturing and retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a stronger-than-expected report on the second quarter
gross domestic product helped raised fears about a renewal of
inflationary pressures.
</P>
