<HEADLINE> Dow Falls 8; Nasdaq Drops 33  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fluctuated Monday as investors remained
uneasy about corporate profits and inflation-- a combination that
led to heavy selling last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average was down 8.24 at 10,503.02 in
the first hour of trading. The Dow lost nearly 75 points Friday and
was down 2 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq was down 32.75 to 3,695.75 Monday after dropping more
than 10 percent last week. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index was off
1.01 at 1,419.48.
</P>
<P>
   The markets were still shaky after Friday's
stronger-than-expected report on the second quarter gross domestic
product raised fears about a renewal of inflationary pressures.
Investors are worried that the inflation-wary Federal Reserve will
raise interest rates again when its policy-writing Open Market
Committee meets later this month.
</P>
<P>
   Disappointing earnings reports also contributed to the market's
depressed mood.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the Dow lower today was Merck, off $1 at $71.25 and J.P.
Morgan, off $1.325 at $129.25.
</P>
<P>
   Internet and consumer stocks also fell, including Kimberly
Clark, off 50 cents at $59.60 and Yahoo!, off $3 at $123.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was down 0.24 at 489.88.
</P>
<P>
   To get a better idea of where the economy and inflation stand,
investors will be closely watching reports this week on consumer
spending, new home sales, manufacturing and retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 109.31 million
shares, down from Friday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 0.70 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.50 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was down 0.61 percent, and France's CAC-40 was
up 0.34 percent.
</P>
