<HEADLINE> Dow Gains 71; Nasdaq Adds 65  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks rebounded Monday as bargain hunters
returned to the market following last week's big decline. But
investors remained uneasy about corporate profits and inflation, a
combination that caused stocks to tumble.
</P>
<P>
   At midmorning on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average
was up 70.54 at 10,581.02. The Dow lost nearly 75 points Friday and
was down 2 percent last week.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq was up 65.19 at 3,777.77 Monday after dropping more
than 10 percent last week. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 Index was up
17.01 at 1,435.45.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is a reaction to last week's sell-off,'' said
Barry Berman, head trader for Robert W. Baird &AMP; Co in Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   He said investors remain nervous about inflation and whether
Federal Reserve policymakers later this month will implement their
seventh interest rate hike since June 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''Up until last week it was pretty much assumed the Fed would
not do anything. But now that is in question,'' Berman said.
</P>
<P>
   The markets were still already nervous about higher rates before
Friday's stronger-than-expected report on the second-quarter gross
domestic product intensified inflation fears and led to renewed
selling. To get a better idea of where the economy and inflation
stand, investors will be closely watching reports this week on
consumer spending, new home sales, manufacturing and retail sales.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the Dow higher Monday was General Motors, up $1 at
$58.25 and General Electric, up $1.50 at $52.50.
</P>
<P>
   Among technology stocks, Oracle rose $2.50 to $75 and WorldCom
was up $1.25 at $38.50
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index was up 1.59 at 491.89.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a narrow margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 272.34 million
shares, down from Friday's pace.
</P>
