<DOCNO> APW20000731.0073 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 14:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> India Movie Actor Kidnapped  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BANGALORE, India (AP) -- A former Indian movie star was kidnapped
with three other men at his home by a well-known criminal gang, the
chief minister of the southern state of Karnataka said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Raj Kumar, in his 70s, gained fame by appearing in more than 200
Kannada-language films over five decades. He is also politically
powerful and is a hero in Karnataka.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar was hosting a housewarming Sunday evening in his home
village of Gajanur, just across the state line in Tamil Nadu, when
a dozen gunmen burst in, kidnapping Kumar, son-in-law S.A.
Govingaraj and two other men, said Karnataka chief minister S.M.
Krishna.
</P>
<P>
   He said the gang was led by the notorious Indian criminal
Veerappan, who uses only one name and has threatened Kumar in the
past.
</P>
<P>
   No clear reason was given for Kumar's kidnapping. Police said
Veerappan is wanted dead or alive.
</P>
<P>
   Stray incidents of stone-throwing and road blockades were
reported in Bangalore, the state capital, and elsewhere in
Karnataka state as news spread of Kumar's kidnapping. Shopkeepers
pulled down metal shutters to protect their windows, bus services
were suspended and schools were closed until Wednesday as a
precaution.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-year-old man was stabbed to death in Bangalore, city police
commissioner T. Madiyal was quoted as saying by Press Trust of
India.
</P>
<P>
   Veerappan began as an ivory poacher, and by 1986 he had become a
full-time smuggler of rare sandalwood from the forests where he
lives. Police accuse him and his gang of killing 36 police and
forest service officers since 1989. He has staged several
kidnappings and released the victims, often for ransom.
</P>
<P>
   Kumar's wife, Parvathamma, said the gunmen had entered the house
just after dinner.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were taken by surprise,'' she said, adding that her husband
told the gunmen, ''I will come with you and talk.'' He went outside
and then the gang leader came into the house and handed her a
cassette, telling her to take it to the chief minister of Tamil
Nadu state.
</P>
<P>
   The audio cassette said only that a representative should
contact the gang's mediator for its demands, Krishna said. The
Tamil Nadu and Karnataka state leaders agreed Monday to send an
emissary to Veerappan.
</P>
<P>
   Members of Parliament expressed anguish in the capital, New
Delhi, over the kidnapping. Authorities were criticized in speech
after speech for their inability to capture Veerappan, although
journalists have interviewed and filmed him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 1406 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000731.0074 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Sentenced to Death  </HEADLINE>
By CHRISTOPHER BODEEN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A Beijing court handed down a death sentence
Monday to a former top official accused of taking bribes, a case
designed to assure Chinese the government is acting to stem
corruption.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng Kejie, who with his mistress amassed $4.9 million from
graft, would be the highest-level politician executed in a long
campaign aimed at assuaging public disgust over corruption and
abuse of power.
</P>
<P>
   The 66-year-old former deputy chairman of the national
legislature was convicted of accepting the bribes while he headed a
poor southern region, the official Xinhua News Agency said in
announcing his sentence by the No. 1 Intermediate People's Court in
Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng has 10 days to appeal, but Xinhua did not say if he would
do so. Appeals in such cases are rarely successful.
</P>
<P>
   In a lengthy report on its main evening news broadcast, China
Central Television showed Cheng sitting in front of a microphone in
a packed courtroom while the prosecution presented evidence,
including numerous documents and a gold watch that was allegedly a
bribe.
</P>
<P>
   As the verdict was announced, Cheng was pulled to his feet by
guards and led from the courtroom, his face expressionless.
</P>
<P>
   ''The amount of bribes Cheng took was extremely huge,'' Xinhua
quoted the verdict as saying. ''The crimes he committed in the
capacity of a senior leading official have ... tarnished the clean
and honest image of government functionaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheng's open trial demonstrated that ''all are equal before the
law'' and illustrated authorities' determination to punish
corruption, the Xinhua report quoted the presiding judge saying.
</P>
<P>
   Pervasive graft and a string of large corruption and smuggling
scandals involving government, police and army officials have badly
damaged public acceptance of the Communist Party's half-century in
power. To restore their image, Chinese leaders have broken with
customary secrecy to announce a series of punishments against
corrupt senior officials, among them Beijing's former party chief
and a deputy provincial governor executed this spring.
</P>
<P>
   The success of the new openness has yet to be gauged. For some
Chinese, the effort has increased suspicions that the corruption
problem reaches into officialdom's highest ranks, and many Chinese
and party functionaries believe Beijing is really using the
campaign to settle scores with officials now in disfavor.
</P>
<P>
   In the Cheng case, prosecutors said he pressured state banks to
issue loans and took kickbacks to approve a range of projects,
plotting with his mistress to amass a fortune for their future
marriage. The proceeds were allegedly deposited in foreign bank
accounts.
</P>
<P>
   He was expelled from the party and dismissed from his
legislative post in April. A party spokesman blamed his downfall on
the ''temptations of women and money.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheng's mistress, Li Ping, and those who paid him bribes have
already been prosecuted, or will face prosecution soon, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   Cheng was caught in a widening investigation into smuggling,
kickbacks and other corruption in Guangxi, a poor southern region
whose rugged coast is a haven for smugglers. Cheng, a member of
China's Zhuang ethnic minority, headed Guangxi's government from
1990-98 and was its deputy Communist Party secretary.
</P>
<P>
   His deputy, Xu Bingsong -- sentenced last August to life in
prison -- had such a penchant for bribes that he was reportedly
known locally as ''millionaire Xu.''
</P>
<P>
   Cheng's case is said to have tainted Li Peng, the party's No. 2
and the head of the national legislature. It was Li who brought
Cheng to Beijing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
