<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Germany Pressured To Stop Neo-Nazis  </HEADLINE>
By PAUL GEITNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- Even before a pipe bomb explosion at a train
station injured 10 recent immigrants, German officials were
bemoaning a lack of public outrage over the increasing number of
attacks against foreigners in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is it a domestic problem, Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder
said, but the constant reports of violence stained Germany's image
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer complained that people seem to
get more upset about attack dogs than neo-Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   ''It makes me unbelievably angry when I read in the newspaper
that murderous attacks are occurring in our country almost every
day against foreigners, strangers or people with another skin
color,'' he told the Berlin-based Tageszeitung.
</P>
<P>
   Now attempts to jolt ordinary Germans out of complacency are
growing more intense as police in Duesseldorf investigate the train
station bombing last week.
</P>
<P>
   As officers distributed fliers through the neighborhood Monday
seeking leads, they stressed that nothing had been ruled out. Yet,
with all 10 victims from the former Soviet Union, and six of them
Jewish, police say xenophobia was a ''conceivable'' motive.
</P>
<P>
   Seven of the injured remained hospitalized, including one man in
critical condition. His wife, who was five months pregnant,
miscarried and nearly lost a leg in the blast.
</P>
<P>
   Expressions of shock and outrage filled German newspapers and
airwaves over the weekend. Yet the violence continued.
</P>
<P>
   Two asylum seekers, from Togo and from Sudan, were insulted,
kicked and chased from a train station in the eastern city of
Eisenach by a gang of neo-Nazi youths, police said. The two managed
to escape and later identified their attackers to police.
</P>
<P>
   Three men, ages 18 to 21, were ordered held Monday on charges
including causing serious bodily harm and incitement to racial
hatred. A fourth, 17-year-old suspect was ordered held in a home
for juvenile offenders.
</P>
<P>
   Interior Ministry spokesman Rainer Lingenthal said the attack
showed ''that violent right-wing extremism is still virulent in our
country.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Cheap statements against anti-foreigner behavior and
announcements without obligations aren't enough by a long shot
anymore,'' said Fritz Kuhn, chairman of the junior coalition
partner Greens party.
</P>
<P>
   The government currently spends about $193 million on projects
designed to promote tolerance and provide youths with alternatives
to gangs.
</P>
<P>
   But Schroeder, noting Germany's ''especially sensitive
situation'' following the Holocaust, said more must be done to
catch and prosecute far-right criminals to the full extent of the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ''The problem can't be solved with social work alone,''
Schroeder said.
</P>
<P>
   A top Interior Ministry official, Cornelie Sonntag-Wollgast,
said she would meet this week with other Cabinet representatives
and state officials to see ''whether federal and state police can
get involved in a stronger way when they see something
suspicious.''
</P>
<P>
   Neo-Nazi Internet sites would also be targeted more vigorously
for shutdown, she added, and one Greens lawmaker even called on
postal carriers to refuse to deliver racist or far-right
publications.
</P>
<P>
   Yet experts and officials stressed that government can do only
so much without greater public involvement, even if it's just
calling police to report potential trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ''People must stop looking away and start seeing what's
happening and getting involved,'' Justice Ministry spokesman Thomas
Weber said.
</P>
<P>
   The head of Germany's internal security agency, Heinz Fromm,
said he has observed a ''large tolerance'' for extremist attacks
against foreigners among segments of the population. While not
everyone who looks on approvingly is an extremist, he said, the
generally muted public outcry only emboldens extremists.
</P>
<P>
   ''The perpetrators ... have the feeling they're acting on behalf
of many,'' Fromm said in the weekend edition of the Sueddeutsche
Zeitung, a Munich-based newspaper.
</P>
<P>
   Out of a country of 81 million, Fromm's Office for the
Protection of the Constitution reports a total of about 9,000
potentially violent neo-Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   His office reported a 5 percent increase in violent crimes
attributed to neo-Nazis last year, to 746 -- including the first
killing in three years. So far this year, three killings have been
recorded.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the neo-Nazi attacks are concentrated in the
economically distressed, former communist east.
</P>
<P>
   But officials noted that three of the youths arrested in the
weekend attack in Eisenach were from the prosperous western state
of Bavaria.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 1421 </TRAILER>
