<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sarajevo's Serb Mayor Sets Standard  </HEADLINE>
By AIDA CERKEZ-ROBINSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) -- Ordered to leave the
apartment where she has lived since her own home was destroyed,
Muslim refugee Murata Karahodzic told Bosnian television she would
have to give up her children unless she found other housing.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the mayor appeared at her door with keys to a new
apartment. And he is a Serb.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his ethnic origins, Ljubisa Markovic is popular among
his Muslim constituents because he has brought a service-oriented
style of government unheard of in the Balkans, known for sluggish
bureaucracy, corruption and indifference.
</P>
<P>
   Markovic, a member of the multiethnic Social Democratic Party,
was elected in April as mayor of Sarajevo Center, one of four
municipalities which form Greater Sarajevo. About 80 percent of his
70,000 constituents are Muslims -- with bitter memories of Serb
shelling and atrocities from the 1992-1995 ethnic war.
</P>
<P>
   With his yellow notebook of promises, a Web site and liberal
visiting hours, Markovic is winning the Muslims over.
</P>
<P>
   ''The relation of the government to the citizens has changed,''
Markovic told The Associated Press in an interview. ''Before the
municipality received them only on Mondays and Fridays. Now, it's
every day. The whole day.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary citizens attend staff meetings where officials plan how
to spend public funds.
</P>
<P>
   Through his Web site, Markovic has invited citizens to send him
e-mails about their problems or to ask about housing, refugee
return or employment.
</P>
<P>
   The municipal administration is setting up a computer system so
residents can obtain birth certificates, permits and other official
documents electronically and by mail within a day.
</P>
<P>
   Presenting problems directly to the mayor in person is no longer
a privilege of business tycoons and the politically well-connected.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor has set aside Tuesday afternoons to receive ordinary
citizens who want help with their problems. He keeps the small
yellow notebook to remind him what he has promised.
</P>
<P>
   Another Muslim constituent, Amela Muratovic, needed help
rebuilding her family's home leveled by Serb shellfire during the
war.
</P>
<P>
   For eight years, her family had found shelter in an abandoned
Serb apartment, but the Serb owners want their apartment back now
that the war has been over for five years.
</P>
<P>
   ''I went to Markovic last week,'' she said. ''I explained my
problem to him, and he wrote down my name. I didn't think much of
it because I know how many people like me turn to him.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days after the meeting, a city clerk came calling. '''We
found a donor who will repair your house,''' Muratovic, 37, quoted
the clerk as saying. '''You will move in by the end of this
year.'''
</P>
<P>
   Housing is among the biggest problems facing city officials
throughout Bosnia. In Sarajevo, an estimated 4,000 refugees from
other parts of the country live in other people's homes.
</P>
<P>
   Most squatters cannot return to their own homes because leaders
of rival ethnic groups refuse to let them or because their property
was destroyed during the war and they have no money for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   Karahodzic, for whom the apartment was found in a day, fled here
from Srebrenica, the eastern Bosnian enclave where Serbs allegedly
massacred thousands of Bosnian Muslims in the final days of the
war. Facing eviction, she said she would have to put her children
in an orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   ''That moment, by coincidence,'' Markovic said, ''the
municipality obtained a small apartment and we solved her
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   He may not be so lucky in the future.
</P>
<P>
   About 7,000 former Sarajevans have asked to return to the city
from areas where they took refuge, but about 65 percent of the
apartments or houses in Sarajevo were damaged during the conflict,
and many others have been taken over by squatters.
</P>
<P>
   Markovic admits he has no easy formula for solving the problem
during his four-year term.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll do my best,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 1432 </TRAILER>
