<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Accused of Milosevic Death Plot  </HEADLINE>
By ALEKSANDAR VASOVIC
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Four Dutch citizens have been
detained in Yugoslavia on suspicion of plotting to assassinate or
abduct President Slobodan Milosevic, the Yugoslav information
minister said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Goran Matic said the four men were arrested sometime in July
when they tried to enter Kosovo from the Yugoslav republic of
Montenegro with plans to ''kill President Slobodan Milosevic or
carry out other terrorist acts.''
</P>
<P>
   Matic, who did not say whether the men had lawyers, showed
footage of the suspects in military uniforms being interrogated by
Yugoslav authorities. One of the men was shown saying he'd plotted
to abduct Milosevic or former Bosnian Serb leader Radovan Karadzic
to ''surrender them to The Hague.''
</P>
<P>
   The footage showed maps, pocket tools, knives and cameras
allegedly used by the Dutch. One of the men was shown saying that
the group intended to abduct Milosevic or Karadzic ''if we come
across them.''
</P>
<P>
   ''We would put them in a ski box (on top of a car) and transport
them to the embassy or out of the country,'' the unidentified
suspect said.
</P>
<P>
   Another said on camera that in case the abduction of Milosevic
failed, one of them ''had the idea to kill the president, to
decapitate his head, to put it in the box and to send it home'' to
the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   Both Milosevic and Karadzic have been indicted by the U.N. war
crimes tribunal in The Hague for atrocities committed by Serb-led
troops in Kosovo and Bosnia, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Matic claimed the arrested men were a part of the ''NATO
military-intelligence community'' who ''used the excuse of being
weekend warriors and adventurers'' when arrested.
</P>
<P>
   He said that the group was trained by special British forces.
</P>
<P>
   The Dutch Foreign Ministry said it was looking into the matter,
while the Dutch defense ministry identified one of the four as
Johannes van Rie, a former army conscript who finished his service
in 1989.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the prosecutor's office of the war crimes
tribunal could not be reached for immediate comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
