<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Putin Accepts Invite To Visit Libya  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW (AP) -- Russian President Vladimir Putin accepted an
invitation Monday to visit Libya, Putin's foreign policy adviser
said.
</P>
<P>
   Libyan Foreign Minister Abdel Rahman Mohammed Shalgam issued the
invitation during a meeting between the two in Moscow, aide Sergei
Prikhodko said, according to Russian media. No date for the trip
was released.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement follows a flurry of official visits by Putin,
including a high-profile meeting with North Korean leader Kim Jong
Il.
</P>
<P>
   Shalgam arrived Sunday for three days of talks, the first visit
by a Libyan foreign minister to Russia. He said Putin had invited
Libyan leader Moammar Gadhafi to visit Russia but did not say
whether the invitation had been accepted.
</P>
<P>
   Shalgam also said he believes Putin ''due to his vigor, youth
and energy, could give Russian foreign policy a fresh impetus that
would allow for the creation of a strong balance of forces in the
world,'' the Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomatic contacts between Russia and Libya were reduced during
the years of international sanctions imposed on Libya in connection
with the 1988 bombing of a Pan Am airliner.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations suspended the sanctions in 1999, and Libya
surrendered the suspects for a trial now under way in the
Netherlands. But the United Nations has not fully lifted the
sanctions, meaning they could be reimposed. Putin called Monday
called for ''a definitive lifting of the sanctions,'' Prikhodko
said.
</P>
<P>
   Moscow, a major supplier of conventional weapons to Libya in
Soviet times, had long pushed for lifting the sanctions, hoping it
would allow Libya to pay off its Soviet-era debt to Russia of about
$2.4 billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
