<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> BC-NY--Job Count Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru,0760  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) - The federal government is investigating New
York state's robust 1999 job-growth numbers following complaints
that the statistics might have been inflated.
</P>
<P>
   In March, the state revised its 1999 job-growth rate from the
original estimate of 1.8 percent to 2.6 percent, an increase that
''looked a little bit unusual,'' said Patricia Getz, division chief
for monthly industrial employment statistics at the federal Bureau
of Labor Statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ''The revisions for New York was larger than what we usually
see,'' Getz said Monday. ''We're just trying to make sure there are
not any errors or any problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Getz said it appears that a lot of the job growth came from a
sudden spurt in the first quarter of 1999, right at the time when
the state Labor Department was instituting processing changes.
</P>
<P>
   The bureau is examining the labor statistics, particularly the
January-March data, to see if there was any connection between the
figures and the processing changes.
</P>
<P>
   Getz said the bureau expects to conclude its investigation in
the next few weeks and decide then whether to ask the state to
readjust its job-growth figures.
</P>
<P>
   Such a revision could be a black eye for Gov. George Pataki, who
in March trumpeted figures showing the state's 1999 private-sector
job creation rate bettering the national rate. Pataki had said that
just under 200,000 jobs were created in New York last year, the
most in 15 years.
</P>
<P>
   The overall job gains in 1999 were the first time - except for
two years in the mid-1980s - when the state gained employment at a
rate faster than the national average in the past 42 years,
according to the Pataki administration.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Kagann, Pataki's chief economist, said that the high
growth rate that's under question is a progressive part of several
years of strong private-sector job increases.
</P>
<P>
   ''For upstate New York, in 1997 it was 1.1 percent. In 1998 it
was 1.7 percent. In 1999, 2.5 percent. The job growth didn't start
in 1999, it started in 1997,'' Kagann said. ''It's a perfectly
normal turnaround. There's nothing unusual about the strength of
the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Federal officials grew suspicious of the state's job figures
when an annual adjustment of the data boosted the state's job
gains. That technical adjustment found an extra 68,450 jobs
statewide, prompting several complaints to the federal agency from
those who doubted the numbers' veracity.
</P>
<P>
   The inquiry into the statistics was first reported Sunday by the
Buffalo News.
</P>
<P>
   The state has acknowledged that some jobs were counted twice.
The mistakes came at a time when the method of processing
unemployment insurance forms for employers was changed.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas A. Rodick, director of research and statistics for the
state Department of Labor, said his office found some duplicate
reports from some companies. Other technical errors could have
occurred when data was scanned into the department's computer
system.
</P>
<P>
   Rodick, however, described the problems, on the whole, as
minimal. The department may be off by about 9,000 jobs, or about
''one-tenth of 1 percent'' of the statewide total jobs figure, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're very, very certain of our information. We're very
comfortable with it,'' Rodick said. ''They're strong, accurate
reports.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that the strong job growth can be expected given a
corresponding decrease in unemployment data - ''Tons of signs that
the economy is doing well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Labor Department has until Sept. 16 to complete all the data
adjustments and submit the final revision to the federal
government. In a statement released Monday, Rodick said he was told
last week by the Bureau of Labor Statistics to submit the numbers
immediately because they were in an ''election cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   Pataki spokesman Michael McKeon said the governor is ''confident
with our numbers.'' He said the federal investigation could be a
move by the Democratic Clinton administration to boost the campaign
efforts of Senate candidate Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has said that upstate's economy is not what it should be
considering the boom in other regions of the country and in the New
York City area. Other New York Democrats have also charged that New
York's economy is not responding well enough to the generally good
times nationally.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's very clear that the Clinton administration is using its
clout to further Hillary's political campaign, and it's just an
outrage,'' McKeon said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-31-00 1509 </TRAILER>
