<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Performer Leaves Wagner Festival  </HEADLINE>
By WOLFGANG HUEBNER
<TEXT>
<P>
   BAYREUTH, Germany (AP) -- A second veteran performer announced
her departure from the renowned Richard Wagner music festival
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Soprano Waltraud Meier's decision to leave at the end of the
season came as the festival's embattled director tried to inject a
bit of optimism by announcing that an American arts patron had
pledged financial support.
</P>
<P>
   Alberto Vilar, an opera fan who made his fortune from
investments in high-tech companies, will contribute a
''substantial'' sum toward a new version of the opera
''Tannhaeuser'' in 2002, said Wolfgang Wagner, the composer's
80-year-old grandson and the festival's director for nearly 50
years.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner declined to name a sum, but said Vilar's contribution is
''an important step toward securing the festival's future.'' He
stressed there were no conditions attached.
</P>
<P>
   Vilar has previously pledged millions of dollars to the
Metropolitan Opera in New York, the Royal Opera in London, La Scala
in Milan, Italy, and the Mariinsky Theater in St. Petersburg,
Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The financial boost comes amid growing criticism of the Wagner
family's grip on the festival, in its 89th year, and a debate about
how it can be brought up to date.
</P>
<P>
   A new production of the composer's landmark Ring cycle, which
pitches the opera's mythical German gods into the industrial age,
has been greeted with mixed reviews, and several of its top
performers have deserted the organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Meier, the internationally renowned soprano who sings alongside
superstars Placido Domingo and Alan Titus in this year's
performance of the Ring, on Monday attacked Wolfgang Wagner's
leadership and said she will follow the example of another top
singer, 29-year Bayreuth veteran Hans Sotin, and quit. Sotin quit
the day before the festival opened, citing artistic differences.
</P>
<P>
   Meier told the Nordbayerischen Kurier newspaper that her 17th
year performing at the festival would be her last, after the
leadership refused to allow her to appear at Bayreuth next year
while also performing at a festival in Munich.
</P>
<P>
   ''To rest on the fact that they could sell every ticket 10 times
is the wrong way to look at it. Bayreuth should get down off its
high horse,'' she said, adding that she expected Domingo also will
throw in the towel.
</P>
<P>
   Wagner rejected the criticism, without going into details.
</P>
<P>
   Further changes may depend on the outcome of a debate within the
Wagner family about who should be the next director. While Wolfgang
Wagner has been pushing his wife and longtime assistant Gudrun as
his successor, one of the composer's great-grandchildren, Nike
Wagner, says an overhaul is needed, including an expansion of the
repertoire from the 10 mature Wagner works -- and even including
operas by other composers.
</P>
<P>
   Two other great-grandchildren of the composer also are competing
to become director. A vote has been pushed back to October.
</P>
<P>
   The 2002 edition of ''Tannhaeuser'' is to be produced by
France's Philippe Arland and conducted by Christian Thielemann. The
2002 festival also will see Wolfgang Wagner's productions of
''Meistersinger'' and ''Parsifal'' phased out, ending his
participation in the festival as a creative director.
</P>
<P>
   This summer's festival opened July 25 and runs to Aug. 28.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.ring2000.de
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 1511 </TRAILER>
