<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rock climber who fell to death identified as a college student from Ky. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   HARDWICK, N.J. (AP) - A rock climber who fell to his death
Saturday near the Delaware Water Gap has been identified as a
22-year-old college student from Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Raible, of Louisville, Ky., fell 120 feet down a cliff
face while descending Mount Tammany, a popular rock-climbing spot
in Warren County, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Raible, a student at Haverford College in Haverford, Pa., and
Todd Garcia, 35, of Allentown, Pa., had completed a 200-foot climb
on a route known as Double Overhang, said Doyle Nelson, chief
ranger at the Delaware Water Gap National Recreation Area.
</P>
<P>
   They were rappelling down the cliff face when the accident
occurred about 6:30 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson said Raible had fastened his climbing rope through a
sling left by previous climbers. It slipped and he plummeted to the
base of the cliff.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia, whom rangers described as an expert rock climber, found
Raible at the base of the cliff, but he was not breathing, Nelson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia then hiked out to Route 80 and flagged down a motorist
who called for help.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
