<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 15:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Governor, Republicans deny report on party battle  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - New York Republicans, including Gov. George
Pataki, flatly denied a published report that a behind-the-scenes
battle is underway to remove state party chairman William Powers.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no truth to it,'' Pataki said Monday. ''Chairman
Powers is a friend of mine and from my standpoint he should be
chairman as long as he wants to be. He's been an outstanding
chairman.''
</P>
<P>
   In its Monday editions, the New York Post said Pataki and his
allies also are looking to strip Powers' control over Victory 2000,
a ''soft money'' fund-raising committee, and give it to Thomas
Doherty, the governor's appointments officer.
</P>
<P>
   Losing control of Victory 2000 would weaken Powers and help
pressure him out of the chairmanship, the Post said in a report
that quoted anonymous sources.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, say New York Republicans asked at their party's national
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's totally not true,'' Powers spokesman Dan Allen said.
''It's a fabrication.''
</P>
<P>
   Allen pointed out that Pataki and Powers appeared together or
within moments of each other at both New York GOP welcoming parties
in Philadelphia on Sunday. That would not have happened if the two
were feuding, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Republican commentator Roger Stone said the question is more
about who controls the millions of dollars that will flow through
Victory 2000 more than the chairmanship. But now that a story about
a possible coup has gone public, Powers probably cannot be removed,
Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think he survives and his survival is not by a small
margin,'' Stone said. ''The county chairmen love him and he hasn't
made any major enemies throughout the party.''
</P>
<P>
   Powers is credited with building the Republican Party into a
fund-raising machine since taking he chairmanship in the early
1990s. Its resources helped get Pataki elected governor in 1994
against Democratic incumbent Mario Cuomo, but the GOP suffered
setbacks in the 1998 elections when incumbent Republican Sen.
Alfonse D'Amato and Attorney General Dennis Vacco both lost
re-election bids.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City Monday, Republican Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said
he didn't know anything more about an alleged move to remove Powers
than was in the Post.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think Bill Powers is an exceptional party chairman. ... He's
been about as successful a party chairman as we've ever had,''
Giuliani said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He helped elect me mayor, played a big role in helping me get
elected. ... He played a very big role in electing George Pataki
governor in 1994.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who nonetheless angered Powers in 1994 by endorsing
Cuomo for re-election, said he supports the chairman ''very
strongly.''
</P>
<P>
   ''I just have tremendous respect for him as a political
professional,'' the mayor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
