<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 15:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McGreevey campaign gets boost from Newark mayor, Senate leader  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Democrat Jim McGreevey's campaign for
governor got the backing Monday of about 30 elected officials,
including Newark Mayor Sharpe James and state Senate Minority
Leader Richard J. Codey.
</P>
<P>
   The show of support here for the Woodbridge mayor included seven
of the state's 21 county Democratic chairmen, dealing a blow to
U.S. Sen. Robert Torricelli, who announced 12 days ago that he
planned to seek the party's nomination for governor next year.
</P>
<P>
   State party chairman Thomas Giblin did not attend, but said
later, ''I think that Senator Torricelli would also have been a
strong candidate, but I think it's kind of critical now that he
re-examine his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   ''His original intent was to serve as a unifying force for the
New Jersey Democratic Party, north and south. That goal doesn't
seem to be attainable. There seems to be grass-roots support for
Mayor McGreevey.''
</P>
<P>
   Torricelli had no immediate response, his office said. He had
said he would run only if he decides the state party will heal its
geographic and personal divisions and unite around him.
</P>
<P>
   James, mayor of the state's largest city and also a state
senator, said a battle leading to the 2001 primary would hurt the
party's efforts to elect Al Gore president and Jon Corzine to the
U.S. Senate this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Noting that McGreevey almost unseated Gov. Christie Whitman in
1997, James said, ''Against all the odds, he's been campaigning to
put a Democrat in the Statehouse. It can be done if we stay the
course.''
</P>
<P>
   James and Codey both said they supported Torricelli for Senate,
but remained committed to McGreevey, whom they backed for governor
before.
</P>
<P>
   Codey described the ''anguish'' of the past two weeks in
considering the candidacies of both men.
</P>
<P>
   ''If you want someone to bring home the bacon, it's Bob
Torricelli. If you want someone to fight for you, it's Bob
Torricelli,'' said Codey, who was joined by several ranking Senate
colleagues, including Raymond J. Lesniak of Union County and John
A. Lynch of Middlesex County.
</P>
<P>
   Codey said he spoke earlier in the day to Torricelli: ''He was
extremely gracious and understanding of my own personal
commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey, 42, who has run nearly non-stop for governor for six
years, took a swipe at his possible challenger while surrounded by
supporters, including mayors from a half-dozen towns in Essex
County and many officials from his base in Middlesex County, where
he heads the state's fourth-largest municipality.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Democratic Party is greater than any individual's
political ambitions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, McGreevey said he had spoken to Torricelli, but said he
had not asked the first-term senator to forgo a statehouse race. He
described the conversation as ''personal'' and declined to
elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   The gathering demonstrated that McGreevey had support from one
end of the state to another and that he was not intimidated by
Torricelli, whose fund-raising prowess led to his leadership of the
Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The county chairmen attending were from Bergen - Torricelli's
base - as well as Atlantic, Cape May, Middlesex, Ocean, Somerset
and Union counties.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, McGreevey had two events to showcase his support from
labor unions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
