<HEADLINE> Group Attacks Indian Army Camp  </HEADLINE>
By QAISER MIRZA
<TEXT>
<P>
   SRINAGAR, India (AP) -- A Pakistani-based rebel group opposed to
a cease-fire in Kashmir attacked Indian security forces in the
disputed state, killing at least three soldiers, officials said
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The assault on the Indian army camp Sunday night was the first
attack since a three-month cease-fire was announced July 24 between
the Indian army and the Hezb-ul Mujahedeen militant group.
</P>
<P>
   Abu Usama, a spokesman for the Pakistani-based Lashkar-e-Toiba,
called The Associated Press on Monday and said the attack was in
retaliation for the cease-fire agreement.
</P>
<P>
   At least three soldiers were killed and five wounded, police
said. The Press Trust of India, however, said six soldiers were
killed. The differing reports could not be reconciled immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Usama said his group killed ''many soldiers'' in the raid.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, suspected militants fired at policemen in a crowded
shopping area in the Kashmir capital of Srinagar, seriously
wounding at least two officers, police said.
</P>
<P>
   In another attack, suspected militants threw a hand grenade at a
paramilitary patrol, wounding two soldiers and three civilians in
downtown Srinagar, police said.
</P>
<P>
   No group immediately claimed responsibility for the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds of Kashmir is controlled by India and the rest by
Pakistan. The two nuclear-armed neighbors have fought two of their
three wars over Kashmir and battled each other with artillery and
mortar fire for 11 weeks last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The violence has killed more than 25,000 people since 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Indian leaders have said that no talks can be held on the
separation of Kashmir from India, arguing that according to the
Indian constitution Kashmir is a part of India.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas say they will not talk to the Indian government
if it puts forward any conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Farooq Abdullah, the highest elected official in Indian-held
Kashmir, said Sunday night he was confident the eventual outcome of
talks would be that Kashmir would remain within India.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
