<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Archbishop Endorses Evangelicals  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD N. OSTLING
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) -- The Archbishop of Canterbury,
speaking Monday to an international conference of evangelical
Protestants, endorsed their belief that ''the Christian faith is as
relevant today as it has ever been, and the need for a Savior is as
urgent as ever.''
</P>
<P>
   George Carey, introduced as a fellow evangelical, leads the
world's 77 million Anglicans and Episcopalians, and is the Church
of England's 103rd primate since the year 597. Yet many listeners
were from far younger and much different churches in the developing
world, where Christianity's demographic future lies.
</P>
<P>
   The conference, summoned by an ailing and absent the Rev. Billy
Graham, announced that 10,287 attendees have come from 209 nations
and territories, confirming this as the largest and most diverse
world meeting of the thriving evangelical movement.
</P>
<P>
   Though the United States has the largest delegation, 2,767,
nearly two-thirds are from outside Europe and North America. The
next biggest delegations, in order, are: India, Ghana, Kenya, South
Africa, Australia, Brazil, Canada and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Carey said Anglicanism prizes open thought but ''the truly
worrying aspect today is a radical liberalism, an enemy to us all,
that denies the teaching of the church down the centuries and
denies the authority of the Scriptures, for 2,000 years the base of
historic Christianity.''
</P>
<P>
   But he warned his conservative audience against lapsing into
fundamentalism, anti-intellectualism or suppression of honest
questioning.
</P>
<P>
   Carey also echoed the evangelicals' insistence that Jesus Christ
was not just a visionary teacher ''but the only Lord and only
Savior.''
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop mentioned obedience to biblical morals but did
not mention the debate among Anglican bishops over homosexuality.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, England's bishops and the Anglican hierarchy worldwide
voted strongly against homosexual activity. But individual bishops
in America's Episcopal Church and several other nations are free to
follow liberal policies, much to the distress of growing churches
in the developing world.
</P>
<P>
   Hours before Carey spoke, a key evangelical Anglican leader told
a media conference the archbishop has been ''very brave'' in
opposing homosexual relations. ''I am certain he will continue''
said the Rev. John Stott, a former London rector and globe-trotting
Bible teacher the past 25 years.
</P>
<P>
   Carey was picketed when he preached in May at the United
Methodist Church General Conference in Cleveland. Dozens of
demonstrators were arrested.
</P>
<P>
   Stott, who had given a major address on the Bible, said the
church must uphold heterosexual monogamy: ''I cannot understand how
anybody who submits to the lordship of Jesus Christ and the
authority of Scripture can come to any other conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Another speaker on Scripture was Graham's daughter, Anne Graham
Lotz of Raleigh, N.C., who has traveled as a Bible teacher since
1988 and is holding her own revival meetings for the first time
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Her father, now 81, is undergoing outpatient treatment at the
Mayo Clinic in Rochester, Minn., after an operation to relieve a
fluid buildup on the brain.
</P>
<P>
   Lotz greeted her father, who is monitoring the meeting by
satellite TV, and said, ''You were all invited by Billy Graham and
when you arrived he was not even here. Were you shaken? I was
shaken. When your life is shaken, don't look at what's shaking you.
Look up!'' she said, pointing heavenward.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees were asked to write thousands of personal messages to
Graham that will be shipped Tuesday to Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: www.amsterdam2000.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 1550 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000731.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bombs Level Colombian Town  </HEADLINE>
By WILL WEISSERT
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- A picturesque mountain town lay in ruins
Monday after rebels detonated explosives in front of a church, a
bank, a clinic and other buildings.
</P>
<P>
   Arboleda, 90 miles northwest of the capital, Bogota, looked as
if it had been hit by a major earthquake. White-walled
colonial-style buildings lay in heaps, with some facades tilting at
crazy angles.
</P>
<P>
   Colombian troops and police searching through the rubble after
the two-day attack by hundreds of rebels found the bodies of at
least eight police officers, part of an estimated 25-member
contingent that tried to fight off the attack for two days. Four
civilians, including the wife of a policeman, were also dead.
</P>
<P>
   At least three survivors were found among the local police
force.
</P>
<P>
   Security forces who arrived in Arboleda on Sunday evening aboard
U.S.-built combat helicopters swept through the green hills outside
town, searching for the rest of the police contingent, believed to
number about 10. The missing officers were feared dead, Colombia's
national police chief, Gen. Ernesto Gilibert, told local radio
stations.
</P>
<P>
   A resident, identified only as Duvan, told Caracol Radio that
hundreds of heavily-armed rebels of the Revolutionary Armed Forces
of Colombia, or FARC, arrived in Arboleda on Saturday. They packed
a van and a car with dynamite and planted gas-bombs around the town
and then detonated the bombs, Duvan said.
</P>
<P>
   The guerrillas then hurled pipe bombs at the local police
barracks to finish off any survivors not killed in the initial
blast which leveled most of the building, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on national television from the wrecked town, police
Col. Norberto Pelaez said 10 police officers were dead, although
officials in Bogota insisted the confirmed number was eight.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll was likely to rise even further, Pelaez said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We believe there are four, five or six other officers that are
victims of this attack,'' Pelaez said. ''This is a sad, sad
tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The rebels abandoned the town, located in a coffee-growing area
in the Andes Mountains, on Sunday and clashed with advancing
government troops. One government soldier was wounded in the
fighting.
</P>
<P>
   Rebel attacks in the last three weeks have killed more than 30
police officers nationwide.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 1551 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000731.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gloomy weather: Cooler, wetter summer helps some, hurts others  </HEADLINE>
By JUDITH FORMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) - Tables are in place, red and yellow
flowers in bloom and waiters ready to serve at the patio outside
Hot Tomato's restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   The only thing missing: the customers.
</P>
<P>
   July's rain has been gloomy - and expensive, manager Lawrence
Popper said Monday. Last week's weather washed out $15,000 in
business for the downtown Hartford eatery, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rain kills us,'' Popper said. ''People do like to sit
outside on the patio.''
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures are cooler and rain more plentiful than usual
throughout southern New England this summer, said Kimberly
McCartney, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service in
Taunton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   While the thermometer reached 90 degrees or higher at Bradley
International Airport on 14 days in July 1999, it happened only
once - on July 10 - last month, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Normal precipitation for July is 3.08 inches at Bradley,
McCartney added, but last month saw 5.2 inches of the wet stuff.
</P>
<P>
   And the forecast for the rest of the week is equally grim:
McCartney predicts more clouds, showers and possible thunderstorms
through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm sure in August we'll rebound,'' she said. ''Summer's not
over. We still have August and September.''
</P>
<P>
   But July is the heart of vacation season and for some, such as
Candace Collins-Boden, executive director of the Provincetown
Chamber of Commerce, the weather is taking a toll.
</P>
<P>
   Tourism is down as much 25 percent in Provincetown and
throughout Cape Cod, Collins-Boden said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely a big difference in how many people are here
compared to last July,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Collins-Boden said local retailers and tourism officials are
growing weary of the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody's a little bit damp and soggy and moldy at this
point,'' she said. ''We really need some sunshine.''
</P>
<P>
   At Killington Ski Area in Vermont, resort spokesman Steve Wright
said visits to the alpine water slides at Pico mountain have been
fewer this year.
</P>
<P>
   ''No one has been all that interested in cooling off,'' Wright
said. ''We've been joking around that if it stays cold we might as
well get the snow-guns out.''
</P>
<P>
   The wet weather also has affected the work of Connecticut's
Department of Transportation, particularly paving and linestriping,
said construction administrator Arthur Gruhn. Last week, nearly 30
cars were damaged on Interstate 84 in East Hartford when an asphalt
ramp connecting a section of newly paved highway to the existing
road deteriorated because of rain.
</P>
<P>
   Others are not complaining.
</P>
<P>
   There may be fewer people in New Hampshire's Lakes Region this
year, but the owner of Hart's Turkey Farm Restaurant in Meredith
said her establishment ''is busier because people have to go
somewhere to get out of the rain.''
</P>
<P>
   ''People are going to the beach less but are eating more and
shopping more,'' Dale Hart said. ''So, it's been pretty good for
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Business at tanning salons has been bright.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eight straight days with no sun will do it,'' said James
Young, general manager of Sun Capsule tanning salon in South
Windsor, Conn. ''People need their sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Mary Lou Long, an employee of Suncenter 2000 tanning salon in
Hyannis, Mass., agreed that cool weather means more customers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're probably as a busy now as we are in the beginning of the
fall,'' said Long, who's worked at the salon for five years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cool temperatures, Fahrenheit Mechanical Services in
Enfield, Conn., has installed a record number of residential air
conditioning units this year, said office manager Debra Barrepski.
She said customers began scheduling appointments as early as May
because of the strong economy and last summer's heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   ''If it had been any warmer, we would have been worse off trying
to get the work done,'' Barrepski said.
</P>
<P>
   A group of construction workers spent their lunch break Monday
relaxing on the benches around Bushnell Park in Hartford under
cloudy skies.
</P>
<P>
   ''The weather stinks,'' said George Johnson of Eastford, Conn.
''The job site is awfully wet, damp and muddy.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the less-than-perfect conditions weren't going to
keep the men from dining al fresco.
</P>
<P>
   ''We rough it,'' Johnson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
