<HEADLINE> US: Fujimori Didn't Outline Plan  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP)-- The State Department expressed disappointment
on Monday that Peruvian President Alberto Fujimori stopped short of
outlining a comprehensive plan for promoting the country's
democratic development.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesman Philip Reeker said that Fujimori, in his inaugural
address last Friday initiating his third term, promised to
introduce legislation to reform the intelligence and security
services.
</P>
<P>
   But he regretted that Fujimori did not have more to say on the
reform recommendations made by a high-level Organization of
American States delegation in June.
</P>
<P>
   Those recommendations included reforms in the judicial system,
protection of human rights and freedom of expression and of the
press.
</P>
<P>
   The OAS recommendations were delivered to Fujimori in June
following an election criticized by the United States, other
countries and many Peruvians as falling short of international
standards.
</P>
<P>
   Reeker also expressed regret over the death of six persons
during inaugural day demonstrations protesting Fujimori's continued
rule.
</P>
</TEXT>
