<HEADLINE> Gubernatorial candidate plans October wedding  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - Woodbridge Mayor Jim McGreevey hopes to win
a four-year term as governor in November 2001. But more than a year
before that, he will be getting hitched for a longer term, his
fiancee said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Dina Matos said they are planning to marry in October. She was
with McGreevey on Monday as he was endorsed by about 30 Democratic
officials from around the state.
</P>
<P>
   Matos has made appearances with McGreevey in the past. The
engagement had not been widely publicized, however.
</P>
<P>
   She said she is a Newark native who now lives in Elizabeth. She
works in the public relations office of Columbus Hospital in
Newark.
</P>
<P>
   Matos, 33, said she met McGreevey, 42, at a fund-raiser three
years ago - a fitting locale for a man who has been running for
governor nearly non-stop for six years. He narrowly lost to
incumbent Christie Whitman in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   McGreevey was still married, but separated, during that race.
His then-wife, Kari, and their daughter, Morag, then 4, had already
moved to Vancouver, Canada, where Kari filed for divorce in May
1996.
</P>
<P>
   The divorce was finalized ''several years ago,'' McGreevey
campaign consultant Brad Lawrence said. He did not immediately have
a more specific date.
</P>
</TEXT>
