<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hijack Passengers Lose Appeal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Five passengers on a hijacked Afghan plane that
landed in Britain earlier this year have lost their appeal against
the government's decision to send them home.
</P>
<P>
   A judge at London's Immigration Appeals Center ruled Monday that
the five, who are seeking asylum in Britain, did not have a
well-founded fear of persecution in Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   The five men, who were not identified by name, were aboard the
Ariana Airlines plane seized by gunmen during an internal flight in
February. The hijacking ended four days later at Stansted airport
north of London with the surrender of the hijackers.
</P>
<P>
   The five are among a group of 31 people appealing a decision by
Britain's top law-enforcement official, Jack Straw, to return them
to Afghanistan. Eleven cases were dismissed last week, while 15
have yet to be heard.
</P>
<P>
   The 16 rejected so far are expected to make a further appeal to
the Immigration Appeals Tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   One asylum applicant, an 18-year-old student, said he feared
being conscripted into the military by Afghanistan's Taliban
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm 18 years old, I should have an education -- forcing me to
fight is an illegal act,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Hubert Dunn dismissed his claim, saying that other men in
Afghanistan were placed in the same situation.
</P>
<P>
   Eight of the plane's passengers were granted refugee status in
Britain. The majority of those on board the plane returned home
voluntarily to Afghanistan after the hijacking.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 1631 </TRAILER>
