<HEADLINE> 50,000 green cards available by lottery  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Fifty thousand permanent-resident U.S. visas
will be awarded through a lottery to people wanting to move to this
country or upgrade their immigration status here, Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani announced Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Applications for the visa lottery, which is run by the U.S.
Department of State, will be accepted between Oct. 2 and Nov. 1.
Those selected by the lottery become eligible to apply for a green
card, or permanent-resident visa.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a very valuable process,'' Giuliani said. ''I wish
that it were more than 50,000 people and I wish that we would
actually make America more open to immigrants. ... This is the
single most important reason for the success of New York -
immigration.''
</P>
<P>
   The visa lottery is designed to expand the number of countries
from which new immigrants come. It is open to anyone overseas or in
the United States, except for residents of the following countries:
Canada, China (not including Hong Kong), Colombia, the Dominican
Republic, El Salvador, Haiti, India, Jamaica, Mexico, Pakistan, the
Philippines, South Korea, Taiwan, the United Kingdom (not including
Northern Ireland) and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Information on how to apply can be obtained from the Department
of State at (202) 331-7199 or http://travel.state.gov or the New
York Immigration Hotline at (718) 899-4000.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani said the visa lottery is free, and warned applicants to
avoid people who ask for money to help with the visa process.
</P>
<P>
   ''Anybody asking for money is trying to defraud you,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
