<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Killer of gas station attendant gets life sentence  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   MORRISTOWN, N.J. (AP) - A man who robbed and killed a Pequannock
gas station attendant in a shooting captured on videotape was
sentenced Monday to life in prison.
</P>
<P>
   John Kenny DiLoreto, 21, was also sentenced to a consecutive
20-year term for robbery, meaning he will have to spend more than
80 years in prison before becoming eligible for parole.
</P>
<P>
   A Morris County jury could not reach a unanimous verdict earlier
this year on whether DiLoreto should receive a death sentence for
killing Pakistani native Mohammad Anjum on April 8, 1998, during a
robbery at his gas station.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors played a videotape of DiLoreto firing at Anjum after
the attendant handed over $250 in cash. Two surveillance cameras
showed the robber firing at the attendant, leaving, then returning
to shoot the attendant several more times after seeing through the
station's window that the first shot didn't injure him.
</P>
<P>
   DiLoreto answered yes or no questions but made no statement to
Superior Court Judge B. Theodore Bozonelis before his sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   DiLoreto pleaded guilty to all the charges against him,
including felony murder and armed robbery, in March.
</P>
<P>
   At his trial, jurors decided that several mitigating factors
existed that prevented a death sentence, including DiLoreto's age
at the time of the killing - 19 - drug addiction and post-traumatic
stress disorder. A defense psychologist also testified that
DiLoreto was sexually abused as a child.
</P>
</TEXT>
