<HEADLINE> West Nile spraying planned in Staten Island, Rockland and Suffolk  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Pesticide spraying was planned for Monday night
and Tuesday in Rockland and Suffolk counties and Wednesday on
Staten Island as part of an ongoing effort to fight the West Nile
virus, health officials said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Rockland County was to be sprayed for mosquitoes from 10 p.m.
Monday through 5 a.m. Tuesday in the town of Clarkstown, including
the village of Upper Nyack and parts of the villages of Nyack and
Spring Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Spraying was also scheduled for Ramapo starting at 11 p.m
Tuesday through 5 a.m. Wednesday. Affected areas include parts of
Spring Valley, Kaser and New Hempstead and all of New Square.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, Rockland county residents can call (914)
364-8990 or visit www.co.rockland.ny.us on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   In New York, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced plans for more
spraying on Staten Island, where 13 dead birds have tested positive
for the West Nile virus. Giuliani said Staten Island appeared to
have more infected birds and mosquitoes than the city's other four
boroughs, which is why spraying has been focused there.
</P>
<P>
   Neal Cohen, the city's health commissioner, said that 10 to 20
percent of Staten Island's mosquitoes survived two earlier rounds
of spraying, and that they were beginning to breed. Tests of birds
and mosquitoes show the virus is still present in Staten Island, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're seeing a reemergence of mosquitoes,'' he said at a City
Hall news conference. ''There's a significant amount of viral
transmission in the borough.''
</P>
<P>
   Spraying of all areas of Staten Island was scheduled for 10 p.m.
Wednesday through 5 a.m. Thursday, weather permitting. Details are
available at (877) WNV-4NYC or www.nyc.gov/health.
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk County canceled aerial spraying scheduled for Monday
night because of rain, but ground spraying was still planned for
parts of Western Oakdale, Eastern Oakdale, Sayville, Bellport
Village and Quogue.
</P>
<P>
   Spraying was planned Tuesday night in Mastic Beach and South
Shirley and late Tuesday afternoon in Point O'Woods and Atlantique
on Fire Island. Details are available at (631) 852-4939 or
www.co.suffolk.ny.us.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials suggest staying indoors during spraying, with
windows shut and air conditioners and fans turned off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
