<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 17:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Search on for school bus drivers  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) - Last year a local school bus company was
so desperate it offered $40,000 to a parent-teacher group if
members could recruit 50 new drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the enticement, the offer netted just nine referrals and
only one permanent driver.
</P>
<P>
   With the start of the new school year just a month away, some
communities are bracing again for a driver shortage. The economy
continues to thrive and bus companies are struggling to attract
people for the part-time driver's jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Unfortunately, we're going to be facing the same situation. I
haven't heard anything that's been done differently,'' said Dudley
Williams Jr., president of the Stamford Board of Education.
</P>
<P>
   Stamford's bus provider, Laidlaw Transit, has blamed a shortage
of drivers for service problems that have plagued the district for
years. Last year, parents complained frequently about late buses or
no buses at all, especially early in the school year.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're literally stealing instructional time from these kids.
It's ridiculous,'' said Wanda Kowalski, co-president of Stamford's
Parent-Teacher Council.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it's fair to the kids. That's the real issue
here,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In Middletown the driver shortage forced high school coaches to
obtain commercial drivers licenses so they could take athletes to
games, said David Larson, who recently retired as superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Larson, who is now executive director of the Connecticut
Association of Public School Superintendents, said the shortage is
statewide.
</P>
<P>
   ''Districts are going without drivers,'' Larson said. ''It's
taking longer to get children to and from school.''
</P>
<P>
   Westport's bus provider, Dattco Inc., has openings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We could usually use seven or eight (more) bus drivers,'' said
Myles MacVane, the local safety supervisor for Dattco.
</P>
<P>
   MacVane said he believes the booming economy has hurt
recruitment efforts by bus companies.
</P>
<P>
   ''Most of these people are trying to support families on a
part-time job driving a school bus, which is very, very
difficult,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In Westport, Dattco's starting pay for drivers is $11.25 per
hour, which increases to $12.45 after a year.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Murphy, spokesman for the state Department of Education,
also said the low unemployment rate has made it difficult to
recruit drivers - and substitute teachers and teacher aides, too,
Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   ''School districts and school bus companies are competing with
other employers for just a limited labor pool,'' Murphy said.
</P>
<P>
   David Martinez, district manager for Laidlaw, said the company
has used radio ads and direct-mail campaigns to attract new
Stamford drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he said, the company is looking for more drivers for the
new school year. About 85 percent to 90 percent of the
approximately 140 drivers needed have been hired so far.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economy continues to be strong, unemployment in Fairfield
County is virtually zero, so it's very challenging to find someone
who meets all the criteria and who is looking for a job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez said Laidlaw requires prospective drivers to take a
drug test, to get a physical examination and to have an excellent
driving record. The company also does criminal background checks.
</P>
<P>
   Some school districts, including Bridgeport, Enfield and
Manchester, say they have not had problems finding enough drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been very fortunate,'' said Manchester School
Superintendent Alan Beitman. ''We have managed to keep the same
drivers employed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
