<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey of park trees planned after beetle infestation is found  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) - Alarmed by the discovery of the Asian longhorned
beetle in three maple trees, officials on Monday ordered a survey
of the city's third largest park to determine if the infestation is
more widespread.
</P>
<P>
   Parks Commissioner Henry Stern said the two Norway maples and
one red maple in 1,200-acre Flushing Meadows Corona Park were found
last week to have holes bored by the destructive insects, requiring
that the trees be taken down, chipped and burned - the only
solution to heading off the spread of the infestation.
</P>
<P>
   It marks the fourth time in five years that the Asian longhorned
beetle has turned up in the city, but the first time in the Queens
park with its thousands of trees.
</P>
<P>
   Stern said the Chinese insect is believed to have entered the
United States in shipping crates around 1996, and has no natural
enemies here. ''If it goes unchecked, it could threaten the entire
northeastern forest of the United States,'' Stern told a news
conference.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, hundreds of streetside trees were removed in the
Greenpoint section of Brooklyn, and similar action was taken after
beetle-damaged trees were found last year in two other Queens
neighborhoods, Bayside and Flushing.
</P>
<P>
   The beetle attacks various species of trees but especially
maples, horse chestnuts, black locusts, elms, poplars and green
ash.
</P>
<P>
   Parks department spokesman Robert Lawson said some 2,800 trees
had been removed by the city to stop the pest, but 4,300
beetle-resistant trees had been replanted. These include oaks,
lindens, sweet gums, bald cypress and sephora, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
