<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court overturns judge who disregarded jury verdict in bias case  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - A jury was right when it sided with a
veteran teacher who claimed her recurring breast cancer made her a
target of discrimination, a state appeals court said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The Denville Township Board of Education must pay the $380,000
in damages a jury awarded and the judge should consider additional
legal fees and interest, the court ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Betsy Blume accepted a job as a vice principal in the district,
but before signing an employment contract she told a superior of
her recent mastectomy and the need for time off to undergo more
treatments.
</P>
<P>
   A year into her new job, Blume learned the cancer had returned
and that more treatment was needed, according to court papers.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1994, the board voted not to renew Blume's contract. In
her lawsuit, Blume alleged that school official Sandra Dohrenwend
was angered by Blume's needs for treatment and influenced the vote.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors agreed with Blume and ordered the cash award. But the
trial judge dismissed the verdict after a motion from the school's
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   In a 46-page ruling Monday, the three-judge panel said Blume
presented enough evidence for any reasonable jury.
</P>
<P>
   ''The jury could reasonably have found that Ms. Dohrenwend
reacted with resentment, anger, and hostility to the recurrence of
Ms. Blume's cancer and her need to undergo a second mastectomy,''
the opinion reads.
</P>
<P>
   ''These feelings were not rationally related to Ms. Blume's
performance, either before or after she entered the hospital,'' the
court said.
</P>
<P>
   Now 54, Blume's health is ''generally OK,'' lawyer Arthur L.
Raynes said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ''She feels vindicated. She feels a great sense of relief and is
very pleased,'' Raynes said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyer Glenn R. Moran, who represented the school district and
Dohrenwend, was unavailable for comment Monday, a secretary at his
office said.
</P>
<P>
   In its opinion, the court also said that the mastectomy
qualified as a disability under the state's anti-discrimination
laws. The laws cover anyone suffering from a physical disability,
infirmity or disfigurement that results from an illness.
</P>
<P>
   ''Blume is handicapped within that definition as a result of the
two mastectomies,'' the court said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-31-00 1719 </TRAILER>
