<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 17:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Combs' Trial Put Off Several Months  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge said Monday that Sean ''Puffy'' Combs'
trial on gun possession and bribery charges will start late this
year or early next year.
</P>
<P>
   After lawyers for Combs and his two co-defendants explained
their commitments for the next several months, State Supreme Court
Justice Charles Solomon told them to return Sept. 13 for a status
conference.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon said that if possible he will set a trial date for late
this year, but if necessary he wants to begin as early as possible
next year.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the judge said, ''If there is any way the case
can be resolved for any of these defendants without a trial, don't
hesitate. I leave that to the lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Combs, 30; his bodyguard, Anthony ''Wolf'' Jones, 34; and Jamal
''Shyne'' Barrow, 19, a Combs rap protege; were arrested early Dec.
27 after Barrow allegedly shot three people in Club New York in the
Times Square area.
</P>
<P>
   Combs is charged with two counts of illegal possession of a
weapon stemming from police discovery of a pistol in the Lincoln
Navigator in which Combs and girlfriend Jennifer Lopez fled the
nightclub. The other count arises from a second handgun allegedly
being thrown out of the vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez, who testified before the grand jury that indicted Combs,
is not charged with anything. She reportedly said that she never
saw Combs with a gun. It is possible that she could be called to
testify at Combs' trial.
</P>
<P>
   Solomon also issued a decision Monday in which he denied Jones'
motion to suppress the gun found in Combs' vehicle and a similar
motion by Barrow to bar the gun recovered from his waistband from
being used as evidence at trial.
</P>
<P>
   The judge agreed with Barrow's lawyer Murray Richman that the
defendant had a right to have his lawyer present when police placed
him in a lineup. Solomon said the prosecution can arrange for an
alternative identification procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Combs is charged with bribery for allegedly offering to pay his
driver $50,000 to claim ownership of the gun in the car. Police
said he tried to sweeten the deal by offering the driver a diamond
ring Lopez had given him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
