<HEADLINE> Rebels Fight Each Other in Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
By LYOMA TURPALOV
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia (AP) -- Russian officials on Monday reported
clashes between rival Chechen rebel groups, who they claim are
weakened by internal friction.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the overnight fighting between members of the
fundamentalist Wahhabi sect of Islam and other rebels was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   The clash broke out Sunday night in the town of Shalazhi, an
official in Chechnya's pro-Russian civil administration told The
Associated Press. The official spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   Wahhabism is a strict Islamic movement based in Saudi Arabia
that has made inroads into Chechnya but is distrusted by most
rebels, who predominantly adhere to Sufism, Islam's mystical
movement. The rivalry has helped to fracture rebel forces trying to
drive Russian troops out of the southern republic.
</P>
<P>
   Hit-and-run rebel attacks have caused heavy military losses and
sapped morale in recent months, and the Russians have bogged down
in their efforts to regain control of the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Radio transmissions intercepted from the rebels indicated that
four fighters were killed in the internal battle, the Russian
command said.
</P>
<P>
   The military also claimed Monday to have killed a top aide to
Chechnya's President Aslan Maskhadov. The Interfax news agency said
Russian special forces troops killed Umar Pashayev, who was in
charge of financial affairs for Maskhadov's government, in a
shootout in the southern Kurchaloi region.
</P>
<P>
   Col. Gen. Georgy Shpak, chief of Russia's paratroop forces,
claimed Monday that his troops seriously wounded both Maskhadov and
a rebel warlord known as Khattab. The claim could not be verified.
</P>
<P>
   Shpak said Maskhadov was wounded two months ago and Khattab was
wounded less than a month ago. It was unclear whether Shpak was
referring to Russian claims made in June that Maskhadov had been
wounded, which were never confirmed. Maskhadov appeared healthy in
a television interview broadcast in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops boosted security Monday at the scores of
checkpoints dotting Chechnya's roads to keep rebel fighters from
entering Grozny in preparation for possible attacks against federal
forces.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the increased security, federal checkpoints came under
fire seven times in Grozny on Sunday, and several Russian soldiers
were wounded, the government official told AP.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Su-25 attack planes and Mi-24 and Mi-6 helicopters flew
46 missions over the past day, the military command said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   A paratroop battalion commander suggested the war could drag on
for months, despite the military's claims that victory is at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ''Paratroopers will stay in Chechnya until next spring at least,
and will crush the militants by any means,'' Lt. Gen. Alexander
Ustimkin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
