<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelans Re-Elect Hugo Chavez  </HEADLINE>
By NIKO PRICE
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela (AP) -- Hugo Chavez won a landslide
re-election, but results indicated Monday that perhaps for the
first time in his presidency he will face a viable opposition to
his reinvention of Venezuela as Latin America's second leftist
regime.
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leaders, long hopelessly fractured, suddenly spoke of
a possible unified front, and Chavez's main opponent in Sunday's
presidential election vowed that his struggle against Chavez's
regime was far from over.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't feel at all that we suffered a defeat,'' said
Francisco Arias Cardenas, who lost the election by 21 percentage
points. ''I now take up a position of struggle to build freedom and
better conditions in the entire country.''
</P>
<P>
   Election results showed that despite a morose economy and
soaring crime, Venezuela's poor majority remains enamored of the
man who has given them hope for a better future. Chavez's victory
celebration early Monday was a raging party, with strangers hugging
one another and dancing in the streets.
</P>
<P>
   ''Every day I feel more proud and more committed to you, my
brothers and my sisters,'' Chavez said.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the presidency, Chavez allies captured 60 percent of the
new, unicameral legislature. But that isn't enough for the
two-thirds needed to rubber-stamp the president's choices for posts
such as the Supreme Court, attorney general and election board.
</P>
<P>
   ''He only has a simple majority, so he'll need to conduct a very
open dialogue,'' said Pedro Palma, head of the Venezuelan American
Chamber of Commerce, which represents more than 1,100 businesses.
He also was heartened by Chavez's post-election appeal to business
leaders.
</P>
<P>
   As results came in from close gubernatorial races, it appeared
the opposition had captured 12 states, compared with 11 for
candidates allied with Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   A close Arias aide, Yoel Acosta, said Arias was prepared to meet
with leaders of Venezuela's more traditional opposition -- which all
but collapsed when Chavez was elected in a December 1998 landslide
-- to form a united front based on their opposition to Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   The largest bloc of opposition votes went to Democratic Action,
which for the last 40 years has dominated Venezuelan politics.
Party leader Timoteo Zambrano said: ''We form part of a new
generation that won't mortgage itself to the government.''
</P>
<P>
   But political analyst Ricardo Sucre said it is doubtful that a
unified opposition could come together, at least in the short term,
because all opposition parties are ''very disoriented.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The opposition parties lack legitimacy, goals and ideological
spaces,'' he said. ''Until they fill those gaps, they won't be a
strong opposition.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
