<HEADLINE> State: Landlord's ad offered apartments to ''whites only''  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A Westfield man posted classified
advertisements on the Internet offering apartments for rent to
''whites only,'' the state alleged in a lawsuit Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Michael J. Matthews posted the ads in January and April on a
personal Web site for three-bedroom apartments in Medford, the
state Divisions of Civil Rights and Consumer Affairs said.
</P>
<P>
   After a black resident saw the ad and reported it to state
officials, Consumer Affairs sent a team of black undercover
investigators to try to rent an apartment from Matthews, state
officials said. Matthews, who is white, told the black
investigators the apartment was unavailable, but later that day
offered to rent the same apartment to a white investigator, the
complaint said.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews later pulled the ad, said Mark S. Herr, director of the
state Division of Consumer Affairs.
</P>
<P>
   ''Racism is on the Internet and whenever it violates state law,
we will attempt to stop it in its tracks,'' Herr said.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews' home number is unlisted. His lawyer, Peter Lange Jr.,
said Monday he would have to consult with his client before
offering a comment.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit seeks compensatory damages and an injunction banning
Matthews from housing discrimination.
</P>
</TEXT>
