<HEADLINE> Kin Urges Tough Kosovo Sentence  </HEADLINE>
By FISNIK ABRASHI
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEBELDE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- Isuf Shabiu had walked five miles
just to find a newspaper with the news that a U.S. soldier had
pleaded guilty to murdering his little sister.
</P>
<P>
   Too poor to pay the 25 cents, the 16-year-old snuck a look at
the Koha Ditore daily at a shop in nearby Vitina. His Albanian
family was living here in Kosovo in January when 11-year-old Merita
Shabiu was brutally sodomized before her lifeless body was buried
in the snow. Her battered body was found several months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I read today in the newspaper that the soldier has admitted to
the act,'' said Shabiu, a tall blond who left school a year ago and
has no job, his hands clasped and head bowed. ''We have no hard
feelings against Americans in general, but that guy should get the
sentence he deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   Isuf's family went to Germany to attend the trial of Staff Sgt.
Frank Ronghi, who is accused of killing the girl. The U.S. Army
arranged for his parents and two of their children to attend, but
he was left at home with his grandmother to keep an eye on the
family's one-story house in the wooded hills outside of Vitina.
</P>
<P>
   A small American flag fluttered from the roof of the two-room
shabby house on a hillside in the small village of a Debelde, some
30 miles southeast of the provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
   Ronghi pleaded guilty to charges of murder, forcible sodomy and
three counts of indecent acts with a child. Prosecutors dropped two
other charges, one of rape and another of sodomy murder. The trial
will continue Tuesday, and a panel of officers will determine
Ronghi's sentence. He faces a maximum of life in prison without
parole.
</P>
<P>
   In Vitina, people were angry that a peacekeeper had turned into
an aggressor.
</P>
<P>
   ''I would sentence him to execution,'' said Ibrahim Hasani, 32,
a local shopkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   But Shabiu said he was simply waiting for more news.
</P>
<P>
   ''Let's see how is he going to be sentenced,'' he said softly,
adding that it would be difficult as the family has neither a
telephone or a radio.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
