<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 18:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> All New Jersey 4-year colleges plan tuition hikes this fall  </HEADLINE>
By NANCY PARELLO
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - College students can expect to pay more
this fall at every four-year college and university in New Jersey,
according to figures supplied by the state Commission on Higher
Education.
</P>
<P>
   The tuition hikes will range from about 3 to 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Princeton University posted the smallest percentage increase at
3.2 percent, while Rowan University had the highest at 10.4
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Tuition costs this coming school year will range from $3,375 at
the Richard Stockton College of New Jersey to $25,430 at Princeton.
That doesn't include room and board.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said tuition continues to climb faster than
inflation primarily because of the cost of upgrading technology,
including outfitting schools with Internet-ready computers, and
higher teacher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   They also said the state needs to send more money to four-year
institutions to help keep tuition down.
</P>
<P>
   ''We continue to encourage (schools) to moderate tuition
increases,'' said Jeanne Oswald, deputy director of the New Jersey
Commission on Higher Education. ''But if we want to continue to
keep our colleges competitive, it's going to require that the cost
goes up.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Goertz, the commission's director of fiscal policy, said
the state is sending about $51.4 million more to New Jersey's 10
public and 14 private institutions for a total of about $1.7
billion. That's about 8 percent more than last year.
</P>
<P>
   ''But while state funding is increasing this year in terms of
dollars, it's a lower percentage of actual school budgets than last
year,'' Oswald said.
</P>
<P>
   This year's funding amounts to 2.5 percent of the schools'
operating budgets, compared to 3.5 percent last year, Oswald said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have long suggested that the state should pay a slightly
larger share of the operating costs for state senior public
institutions,'' Oswald said, adding the state should shoulder
two-thirds of the cost, with tuition financing the rest.
</P>
<P>
   But Jayne O'Connor, spokeswoman for Gov. Christie Whitman, said
the state already makes a substantial investment in colleges and
universities.
</P>
<P>
   ''The argument is, the more (colleges) spend, the more they
expect the state to pay,'' O'Connor said. ''While we want to make
college affordable for New Jersey students, if there's no end to
how much the colleges spend, taxpayers can't be expected to
continue to foot the bill. At some point, they need to start
looking within if they want to keep tuition down.''
</P>
<P>
   The College of New Jersey is among the schools posting the
smallest increases. Sue Long, college spokeswoman, credits
frugality.
</P>
<P>
   ''This institution has done a fantastic job of really
scrutinizing every dollar that we spend,'' Long said. ''We're also
taking advantage of a good bond market for our long-term projects.
It's just really tightly controlling our costs.''
</P>
<P>
   At Rowan University, students and faculty decided to raise
tuition at least 10 percent for five years to improve programs and
facilities, said Joe Cardona, university spokesman. This is the
last year for that increase.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've added 39 faculty positions, six new master's programs,
10 new technology positions and more computer labs on campus,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Montclair University has the second highest hike at 10 percent,
but still offers one of the least expensive educations in the
state, with an annual tuition of $3,470. Only Stockton has a lower
tuition at $3,375.
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey is not alone in higher tuition costs, according to
Janice Gams, spokeswoman for the College Board.
</P>
<P>
   She said schools across the nation are routinely raising
tuition. But there has been a trend toward lower hikes since the
mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994-95 school year, tuition increases averaged 6 percent
across the nation. That dropped to 3.4 percent in 1999-2000, she
said. No national figures were yet available for the coming school
year.
</P>
<P>
   ''Colleges are possibly trying to hold the line on prices as one
way they can attract students,'' Gams said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-31-00 1802 </TRAILER>
