<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 18:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feds Make Hair Co's Sell Brands  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- To eliminate antitrust problems, hair care
companies L'Oreal USA Inc. and Carson Inc. will have to sell off
two brands of hair relaxers, the Justice Department announced
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   French-owned L'Oreal had declared plans to acquire Carson, based
in Savannah, Ga., for $79 million in cash. Regulators objected that
the deal would leave L'Oreal in control of 50 percent of the
women's hair relaxer market with three of the top five best-selling
brands.
</P>
<P>
   ''The deal as originally proposed would have resulted in higher
prices for consumers,'' said Joel Klein, assistant attorney general
in charge of the department's antitrust division. ''These
divestitures will protect competition in the marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   The two brands are Carson's ''Gentle Treatment'' and ''Ultra
Sheen'' products, sold throughout the United States. Together, they
account for approximately 14 percent of sales of all women's hair
relaxer kits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
