<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 18:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Albright Stops at Vatican  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME (AP) -- U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright stopped
off here on the way home from Asia on Monday for meetings at the
Vatican, hoping to win its help to break the deadlock over
Jerusalem between Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican has considerable influence with the Palestinians,
who demand sovereignty over east Jerusalem for the capital of their
hoped-for state.
</P>
<P>
   The issue of Jerusalem was a chief cause in sinking July's
U.S.-mediated Israeli-Palestinian talks at Camp David.
</P>
<P>
   Albright, who arrived in Italy late Monday, is to talk Tuesday
with the Vatican's Foreign Minister, Archbishop Jean-Louis Tauran.
She also is to meet with Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini.
</P>
<P>
   In February, the Vatican and the Palestinians signed a strongly
worded accord insisting on an ''equitable solution'' for Jerusalem,
based on international resolutions. It called for international
safeguards of freedom of religion.
</P>
<P>
   The Vatican has long been pushing for a say in the final status
of Jerusalem, home to holy sites of Jews, Christians and Muslims.
</P>
<P>
   Albright initially had been scheduled to return directly to
Washington, but changed her plans over the weekend in Tokyo to
travel to Rome.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
