<HEADLINE> Latest ad from Clinton campaign  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   An analysis of the newest ad from Hillary Rodham
Clinton's
Senate campaign, criticizing a Republican ad that featured photos
of Rep. Rick Lazio and Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan side by side.
<TEXT>
<P>
   TITLE: ''Deception''
</P>
<P>
   LENGTH: 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCER: Mandy Grunwald and ''Team Hillary.''
</P>
<P>
   AIRING: Upstate.
</P>
<P>
   SCRIPT: Announcer: Have you seen this new Republican ad?
</P>
<P>
   It uses spliced pictures to suggest that Senator Moynihan
supports Rick Lazio... He's (Moynihan) endorsed Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   Moynihan: I think she's going to go all the way. I mean to go
all the way with her.
</P>
<P>
   Announcer: Senator Moynihan asked Lazio to have the Republican
ad withdrawn. He calls it ''fakery.'' Lazio's response?
</P>
<P>
   Lazio (in news footage): I had nothing to do with it. I haven't
even seen the ad.
</P>
<P>
   Announcer: But newspapers tell Lazio they're sick and tired of
those kind of excuses ... stop the deception. Rick Lazio ... be
straight with New Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   IMAGES: Footage from the Republican ad is shown picturing Lazio
and Moynihan side by side on a split screen, followed by a clip
from the launch of Clinton's campaign, where she stood beside
Moynihan on his upstate farm. A story from the Albany Times-Union
headlined ''Moynihan wants Lazio ad withdrawn'' is shown, followed
by two clippings of editorials, one from the Syracuse Post-Standard
headlined ''No more deception'' and another from Newsday headlined
''Lazio ad is misleading, Republicans should yank it.''
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: This commercial is a counterpoint to an ad run by the
Republican Leadership Council that features footage of President
Clinton thanking Moynihan, Lazio and others at a ceremony in
Washington for their work on legislation to help disabled
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican ad also uses a split-screen image of a picture of
Lazio next to a picture of Moynihan. The composite prompted
Moynihan to ask Lazio to have the ad withdrawn. ''The ad is
misleading,'' Moynihan wrote.
</P>
<P>
   The Lazio campaign points out that it is not legally responsible
for the content of RLC ads. The RLC has defended the ad as a
legitimate use of the president's public praise for Lazio.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton ad seeks not only to rebut the RLC ad, but also to
suggest to voters that deception by the first lady's opponent is
not limited to this ad.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio spokesman Bryan Flood responded to the new Clinton ad by
saying: ''The only route her campaign knows how to take is to
attack and distort.''
</P>
<P>
   ---
</P>
<P>
   AdWatch analysis by Associated Press Writer Beth J. Harpaz.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-31-00 1834 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
