<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Owner of Destroyed Plant To Sue  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE GEDDA
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Sudanese owner of a pharmaceutical plant
destroyed by U.S. cruise missiles is seeking $50 million in
compensation on the ground that his Khartoum factory was targeted
because of false charges that it had terrorist links.
</P>
<P>
   Salah Idris, who purchased the al-Shifa plant five months before
the August 1998 bombing, will file a civil action suit in the U.S.
Court of Claims in hopes of obtaining restitution.
</P>
<P>
   He has retained the Washington law firm of Jones, Day, Reavis
and Pogue, which said in a statement that Idris will establish that
al-Shifa was ''engaged only in pharmaceutical processing and
packaging,'' with no connection to international terror.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton ordered the attack, alleging that the plant
had links to Osama bin Laden, exiled Saudi-born millionaire
suspected in the bombings of U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania
on Aug. 7, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The retaliatory attack against the Khartoum facility was two
weeks later, coupled with cruise missile strikes against alleged
terror camps in Afghanistan said to have been under bin Laden's
control.
</P>
<P>
   The statement by the law firm said the U.S. government has
retreated systematically from declarations that high officials made
two years ago to justify the attack on the plant, ''except for the
claim that a chemical component of VX nerve gas known as Empta was
found in a soil sample taken by a foreign agent near the plant.''
</P>
<P>
   It added that a study commissioned by Idris found no trace of
Empta in the ground soil and drainage sludge at al-Shifa but
instead found evidence of common pesticides with ''chemical
similarity'' to Empta.
</P>
<P>
   Idris said he has always opposed terrorism as a tool of
political action, has never met with bin Laden and has not
knowingly done business with him or any of his associates.
</P>
<P>
   In its most recent comment on the issue, State Department
spokesman Philip Reeker said last week the administration stands by
its initial justification for the bombing. He said evidence
suggests that bin Laden was seeking to acquire weapons of mass
destruction, including chemical weapons, for use against American
targets. He said Empta, used to make chemical weapons, was found
outside the al-Shifa facility.
</P>
<P>
   ''In the nearly two years since the attack, the evidence about
the purpose of this chemical plant remains persuasive,'' Reeker
said.
</P>
<P>
   Idris said he understands the need of the U.S. government to
defend itself against acts of terror. ''But a government becomes
what it fears most when it lashes out against the innocent and then
fails to recognize its errors and make full restitution,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sudanese government backs Idris's claims that the plant was
not carrying out illicit activities and has demanded that a U.N.
fact-finding mission be established to investigate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-07-31-00 1854 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000731.0153 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 18:59 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Patrick McGahn, a founding father of A.C. casinos, dead at 72  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN CURRAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTIC CITY, N.J. (AP) - Patrick T. ''Paddy'' McGahn Jr., a
flamboyant, tough-talking lawyer who helped sell New Jersey voters
on casino gambling in 1976, has died. He was 72.
</P>
<P>
   McGahn, brother of the late state Sen. Joseph McGahn, suffered a
stroke Thursday and never regained consciousness. He died Sunday at
Shore Memorial Hospital in Somers Point.
</P>
<P>
   The son of an Atlantic City saloonkeeper, McGahn was a decorated
Korean War veteran who went on to become a Democratic Party
operative active in local, state and national campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a larger-than-life character, that's the best way to
describe him,'' said lawyer John Donnelly, a longtime friend. ''He
was constantly on full-tilt boogie, never at a loss for words or an
action plan.''
</P>
<P>
   A native of Pleasantville, he graduated from Mount St. Mary's
College and New York Law School before serving in the U.S. Marines
in Korea, where he won the Navy Cross for bravery, a Bronze Star,
three Purple Hearts and numerous citations as a lieutenant with the
1st Marine Division.
</P>
<P>
   He also earned the nickname ''Piano Wire Paddy'' for the silent
weapon he is said to have used to strangle enemies during
hand-to-hand combat.
</P>
<P>
   McGahn served as an advance man during the 1960 presidential
campaign of John F. Kennedy and the 1968 campaign of Robert F.
Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, he recruited and fielded Democratic candidates,
including his brother, who defeated state Sen. Frank S. ''Hap''
Farley, a longtime GOP power broker, in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   In 1974 and 1976, he was a driving force behind the Committee to
Rebuild Atlantic City, a group of local businessmen and political
leaders who helped persuade New Jersey voters to approve casinos
for Atlantic City.
</P>
<P>
   ''More than anything else, he was an Irish chieftain, which
means he was intensely loyal to his friends, but it also means that
he had grudges and sometimes forgot why he had them,'' said
Atlantic City Mayor James Whelan. ''He was a tough guy, the classic
Marine. When you got past the toughness and it came to the things
he cared about - his family, his friends - he had the proverbial
heart of gold underneath.''
</P>
<P>
   McGahn served as counsel to Resorts International, the first
casino to open here. Later, he was co-director of security for the
1984 and 1988 Democratic National Conventions.
</P>
<P>
   More recently, he was part of a group of veterans who obtained
land for a Korean War Memorial at Boardwalk and Park Place in
Atlantic City. It is currently under construction.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was a real Marine. He just had that Marine attitude and
toughness,'' said Frank J. Siracusa, an insurance broker who worked
with McGahn on the committee.
</P>
<P>
   McGahn, of Margate, is survived by his wife, the former Mercedes
Walsh; daughters Teresa M. Holzman, Catherine McGahn and Patricia
J. McGahn, and son Timothy Patrick McGahn, as well as six
grandchildren and one great-grandchild.
</P>
<P>
   A funeral Mass will be held at 7 p.m. Wednesday at Our Lady of
Sorrows Roman Catholic Church in Linwood, with burial Monday at
Arlington National Cemetery in Arlington, Va.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-31-00 1859 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000731.0154 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> With BC-NJ--Turnpike Shooting, Bjt  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   A chronology of events in the New Jersey State Police
racial
profiling controversy:
<TEXT>
<P>
   - April 23, 1998: Troopers James Kenna and John Hogan fire on a
Dodge Caravan containing four minority men from New York on the New
Jersey Turnpike in Mercer County. Troopers claim van was backing up
to strike them.
</P>
<P>
   - Nov. 19: Burlington County Acting Prosecutor James Gerrow
announces start of grand jury proceedings in the case.
</P>
<P>
   - Feb. 28, 1999: Gov. Christie Whitman fires State Police
Superintendent Carl Williams after published remarks in which he
linked drug trafficking to minorities.
</P>
<P>
   - April 9: Statistics show dramatic drops in arrests and
summonses by troopers in an apparent protest over Williams' firing.
</P>
<P>
   - April 10: Officials close section of turnpike near Exit 7A to
re-enact shooting on tape for the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   - April 13: The Legislative Black and Latino Caucus conducts
first of three public hearings with witnesses testifying about
racial profiling incidents. The caucus eventually calls for outside
civilian oversight of the State Police.
</P>
<P>
   - April 19: A state grand jury indicts Troopers Kenna and Hogan
on charges they lied about the race of motorists they pulled over,
falsifying records and conducting illegal searches.
</P>
<P>
   - April 20: Attorney General Peter Verniero releases report that
says racial profiling is ''real, not imagined.'' The report
acknowledges blacks are not only pulled over more often, they are
far more likely to be searched.
</P>
<P>
   - April 26: Lawyers at the U.S. Justice Department conclude they
have sufficient evidence for a civil rights lawsuit against the New
Jersey State Police, triggering negotiations on a ''consent
decree'' to avoid litigation.
</P>
<P>
   - July 2: Attorney General John Farmer issues second State
Police report detailing poor handling of citizen complaints and
racial discrimination within ranks.
</P>
<P>
   - Aug. 8: Whitman says Carson Dunbar, an FBI administrator in
New York and a former state trooper, is her choice to head the
State Police.
</P>
<P>
   - Aug. 27: The Black and Latino Caucus schedules a hearing for
Aug. 30 giving minority troopers a chance to testify about racial
discrimination within the State Police. A letter to the troopers
from acting Superintendent Michael Fedorko reminds them of
regulations against disclosing confidential information. Some
regard the letter as a threat to discourage those who might have
considered testifying.
</P>
<P>
   - Sept. 7: State grand jury indicts Hogan and Kenna on charges
of attempted murder and aggravated assault.
</P>
<P>
   - Sept. 20: Whitman announces appointment of FBI administrator
Carson Dunbar, a former state trooper, as the new superintendent of
the State Police. He is the first black man to hold the post and
the first to come from outside the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   - Dec. 22: U.S. Justice Department and Farmer announce
settlement of a ''consent decree'' requiring appointment of an
independent monitor to investigate compliance with an agreement to
take steps ensuring there is no racial discrimination. U.S.
District Court Judge Mary L. Cooper is assigned to monitor the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   - Jan. 14, 2000: New Jersey Superior Court judge refuses state
request to postpone civil lawsuit proceedings until Hogan and Kenna
criminal trial is completed.
</P>
<P>
   - April 17: Defense motions claiming driver of the van told a
grand jury he may have stepped on accelerator filed. Lawyers allege
Attorney General's office misled grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   - May 31: Prosecutors respond in court papers that detailed
evidence backs their allegations.
</P>
<P>
   - June 27: State Superior Court Judge Andrew J. Smithson hears
lengthy arguments on motion to dismiss charges.
</P>
<P>
   - Aug. 3: Date Smithson said he would issue his ruling on
defense request.
</P>
</TEXT>
