<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Envoy Tours Arab Countries  </HEADLINE>
By SUSAN SEVAREID
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Egypt (AP) -- The U.S. State Department's top Middle
East expert consulted with Egyptian leaders Monday on how to push
the Israeli-Palestinian peace process forward after the failure of
the Camp David summit.
</P>
<P>
   Assistant Secretary of State Edward Walker, whose stop in Egypt
was the start of a tour of at least a dozen Arab nations, has a
tough task: garnering support for the U.S. argument that the
Palestinians need to make concessions in their talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's very useful that everyone has a chance to think
through what went on at Camp David -- what was accomplished and
those few things that haven't been accomplished yet and how to
approach them,'' Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   But Egypt, which in 1979 became the first country to sign a
peace treaty with Israel and has emerged as a key regional
mediator, appeared reluctant to press the Palestinians over
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of Jerusalem was the main issue causing the collapse of
the Palestinian-Israeli summit, mediated by President Clinton, last
week at Camp David, Md.
</P>
<P>
   Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr Moussa was asked Monday whether
Egypt and Jordan -- two of Washington's closest Arab allies -- will
help the United States persuade the rest of the Arabs that there
could be less than full Palestinian sovereignty over east
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   He replied, ''I don't think that we can enter into this business
of less than full sovereignty. And for whose sake? For whose
interest? It is not our job to do that. Our job is to save the
peace process, to help the United States apply international
legitimacy and resolutions of the (U.N.) Security Council.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker met in the Mediterranean city of Alexandria with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak, Moussa and other Egyptian officials.
Mubarak later held talks with Jordan's King Abdullah II in
Alexandria, part of a flurry of meetings between Arab leaders in
the wake of the summit.
</P>
<P>
   In Rabat, Morocco, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat said Monday
that Middle East peace talks had reached a ''dangerous and
difficult phase of the negotiations, not only on Jerusalem but for
the whole Palestinian issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, who arrived in Morocco for talks with King Mohammed VI
as part of a tour aimed at drumming up support for Palestinian
stance, said he told the monarch that the ''intransigent position
of Israel on the question of Jerusalem'' led to the collapse of the
Camp David talks.
</P>
<P>
   Arabs have been angered by recent American comments, including
hints from Clinton that he would reward Israel for offering
concessions at the summit by moving the U.S. Embassy in Israel from
Tel Aviv to west Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Camp David talks, Arab leaders made clear that
the fate of Jerusalem is not a Palestinian issue alone. Mubarak was
among several Arab leaders who insisted on Palestinian sovereignty
over east Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   ''Saudi Arabia renewed its stance for the return of Jerusalem to
Arab sovereignty and its place as the capital of an independent
Palestine,'' said a statement Monday from Saudi Information
Minister Fouad al-Farsi.
</P>
<P>
   Moving the U.S. Embassy would be seen by many Arabs as
acceptance of Israel's claim to Jerusalem. Most countries have
refused to open embassies in the city.
</P>
<P>
   The Islamic Jihad, a Palestinian opposition group, said moving
the embassy would be ''a war declaration'' and threatened ''direct
retaliation.'' The militant Hezbollah guerrilla group said Sunday
that a U.S. Embassy in Jerusalem would be attacked and the
Americans sent home ''in coffins.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker's two-week tour will include stops in Morocco, Tunisia,
Saudi Arabia, Jordan, Syria, Lebanon, Oman, Qatar, Bahrain, Kuwait,
Yemen and perhaps other nations.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has visited France, Saudi Arabia and Yemen to press his
case. After Morocco, he headed Monday to Tunisia and was then
scheduled to visit Algeria.
</P>
<P>
   There has been speculation that the consultations are a run-up
to another summit to try to secure a final peace agreement before
Arafat's Sept. 13 deadline for the declaration of an independent
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   Mubarak, Abdullah and Clinton all have said they would be
willing to help bring the two sides together again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
