<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 19:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Six more dead crows found to be infected with West Nile virus  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Tests show six more crows found dead in
northern New Jersey had been infected with the West Nile virus,
including the first ones found in Union County.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, 15 crows infected with the potentially deadly virus
have been found dead this year, the state Department of Health and
Senior Services said Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Ten of the birds were found in Bergen County, two each were
found in Middlesex and Union counties, and one was found in Hudson
County.
</P>
<P>
   So far, no humans have been found to be infected with the virus
from the Middle East, which killed seven New Yorkers when it first
surfaced in the region last year.
</P>
<P>
   Along with spraying to control mosquitoes in North Jersey,
health officers in five counties - Bergen, Essex, Hudson, Passaic
and Union - have begun calling their local hospitals to check for
possible cases among the patients.
</P>
<P>
   The virus causes only flulike symptoms in healthy people, but
can be very dangerous for the elderly, children under age 5, and
anyone else with a weak immune system.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the federal Center for Disease Control and Prevention
expects to get test results on 2,000 to 3,000 mosquitoes its
workers collected earlier this month from each New Jersey County.
Results on samples taken from several hundred birds in each county
also are due soon.
</P>
<P>
   To date, samples from 405 mosquito pools and from ''sentinel''
chicken flocks in all 21 counties have not detected the virus this
year. Unlike crows, the chickens are caged, so if any do test
positive, authorities could be sure the virus was present in that
immediate area.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
