<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man admits selling large amounts of drug used to make 'meth'  </HEADLINE>
By JEFFREY GOLD
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. (AP) - A New York man admitted Monday he sold large
amounts of a drug used to make methamphetamine to a Passaic County
man.
</P>
<P>
   In pleading guilty to a single conspiracy count, George P.
Clear, of Hudson Falls, N.Y., said he would cooperate with
investigators and testify against his co-defendant, Mahmoud
Attallah, of Clifton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   In return, prosecutors agreed to drop the other charge Clear
faced, distributing pseudoephedrine.
</P>
<P>
   Attallah pleaded innocent to those charges. No firm trial date
has been set, Assistant U.S. Attorney Michael Buchanan said.
</P>
<P>
   Clear, 43, faces up to five years in prison and a $250,000 fine
when sentenced Nov. 6 by U.S. District Judge William H. Walls.
</P>
<P>
   The scheme appeared lucrative, netting $850,000 and a 2000 Range
Rover in about a year, according to the indictment against Clear
and Attallah, which seeks the money and the vehicle as proceeds of
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities were unavailable Monday to discuss the scope of the
case. Buchanan declined to comment and a message seeking comment
from the Drug Enforcement Administration, which investigated, was
not immediately returned.
</P>
<P>
   Clear admitted that from March 1999 to March 2000 he sold large
amounts of pseudoephedrine to Attallah and unnamed others who were
not registered with the DEA to handle the drug.
</P>
<P>
   Clear had such a registration through G.P.C. Distributing, a
company he operated from his home, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The company, directly or through straw purchasers recruited by
Clear, bought 368,217 bottles of pseudoephedrine - containing over
28 million tablets - from March 15, 1999 to Feb. 25, 2000,
according to court papers filed by the DEA.
</P>
<P>
   Attallah paid cash for the drug, which Clear obtained from
pharmaceutical manufacturers, Clear admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Clear delivered it to a warehouse space that Attallah rented in
Clifton, and Attallah then sold it to others, Clear admitted.
</P>
<P>
   Attallah rented the space using the business name, ''National
Arabic Television,'' which tax returns, bank records and other
documents show is actually a front for distributing
pseudoephedrine, according to court papers filed by the DEA.
</P>
<P>
   DEA documents say methamphetamine, also known as ''meth'' or
''speed,'' is a dangerous, sometimes lethal and unpredictable drug,
and ''represents the fastest growing drug threat in America
today.'' Pseudoephedrine is an ingredient in the production of
methamphetamine.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: U.S. attorney's office in Newark:
http://www.njusao.org/break.html
</P>
<P>
   DEA: http://www.usdoj.gov/dea/index.htm
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
