<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Arrested in Airport Seize  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   HONG KONG (AP) -- A Myanmar man armed with a fake pistol held a
female airport employee hostage aboard a Cathay Pacific Airways jet
for several hours at Hong Kong's airport until surrendering to
police early Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The man evaded security guards at the airport cargo handling
area and seized the woman, an airport cleaner, before running on
board the plane late Monday, police commander Mak Man-poon said.
</P>
<P>
   Only a maintenance engineer was inside the plane at the time, he
said. Radio Hong Kong said the engineer locked himself in the
cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   At one stage, the hostage-taker threatened to kill the woman, a
Nepalese, if police did not withdraw from the area, and expressed a
desire to return to Myanmar, Mak said.
</P>
<P>
   The plane was cordoned off by police at Chek Lap Kok airport,
and they negotiated with the man by mobile phone until he
surrendered shortly after midnight in the early hours Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The hostage-taker has worked as a laborer since arriving in Hong
Kong last year from Myanmar, also known as Burma, police said. He
was being questioned by police, who did not release his identity.
The airport worker was released unharmed, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 747-400 was empty because it was several hours until
the plane was to depart for Paris, the airline said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time that police had to deal with a hostage
crisis at the airport, which was opened in 1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
