<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> West Nile crows spread dead bird paranoia across Northeast  </HEADLINE>
By LISA LIPMAN
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) - Health officials don't want to minimize the
concern the public has over the spread of the potentially deadly
West Nile virus. But some people are taking it to extremes.
</P>
<P>
   Since two crows tested positive in Massachusetts last week for
the virus, officials have been alerted to hundreds of dead birds
that people fear might have died of the virus.
</P>
<P>
   There was one bird that had been mauled by the family cat. Two
birds that had been shot to death. Even a bat that was found dead
in a toilet.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think we told that guy to get rid of it or flush it,'' Steve
Crosby, director of Boston's animal control, said.
</P>
<P>
   Officials said Monday the concern should be more about
controlling mosquitoes, which spread the virus to humans, than
about dead birds.
</P>
<P>
   ''People's risk is very, very low,'' said Valerie Bassett, a
policy writer at the Boston Health Department. ''Certainly people
shouldn't be afraid, but we want to make sure they know the
precautions people could take.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the virus killed seven people and sickened more than
60 in the greater New York City area. So far this year, no human
deaths have been reported. A mosquito carrying the West Nile virus
has been found in Orange County, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The virus is fatal in only a few people who contract it. The
West Nile virus can cause encephalitis, a dangerous swelling of the
brain which can be deadly. Most who contract it experience flu-like
symptoms and never realize they have been exposed to the virus.
</P>
<P>
   There has been an extensive effort to combat the virus, which
has also been found in New Jersey, Connecticut and Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   Those efforts also have raised the concerns of environmentalists
and others who say the pesticide used to control the mosquitoes is
harmful. Orange County, N.Y., plans to drop larvicide to kill
mosquito eggs in all the county's 20,000 municipal storm drains and
to distribute about 30,000 containers of free insect repellent
through local pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, New York City's Central Park was sprayed with
pesticides.
</P>
<P>
   Public service ads will be airing in 185 movie theaters in 11
at-risk counties in New York to educate people about the virus. The
ads will instruct people how to prevent mosquito bites.
</P>
<P>
   A group of Long Island Sound lobstermen based in Connecticut
contend that pesticide is killing millions of lobsters. So far,
there is no definitive proof of their claim. But the Western Long
Island Sound Lobster Association has hired researchers to
investigate if the pesticides caused the number of lobsters caught
to drop more than 50 percent in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Wildlife in Massachusetts also voiced concerns
that pesticide spraying on a pond could harm the freshwater
three-spine stickleback, one of nine endangered or threatened
species of fish in the state.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials in Massachusetts are attempting to keep
residents calm while advising them to use insect repellent, to wear
socks, shoes and long-sleeved shirts, and to remove sources of
standing water around their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Those precautions don't necessarily include worrying about dead
crows, says Dr. Kevin J. McGowan, curator and senior research
associate in charge of the ornithology and mammalogy collections at
the Cornell University Museum of Vertebrates.
</P>
<P>
   ''You should not worry about having a dead crow in your
backyard. You should be worried about having mosquitos in your
backyard,'' McGowan said.
</P>
<P>
   He pointed out that crows don't move around with the virus -
they die from it.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're the victims here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Though fear of animals with West Nile virus appears to be on the
rise, most people don't seem to be concerned about the threat to
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was driving past marshlands yesterday and it crossed my
mind, but then I didn't think any more about it,'' Jim Mulcahy, of
Boston, said Monday. ''I wouldn't go walking through those
marshlands, though.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
