<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rev. Al Sharpton to appear at GOP convention  </HEADLINE>
By JESSE J. HOLLAND
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) - One of the last people in the world one
might expect to appear at the Republican National Convention will
show up with a written invitation, Al Sharpton. And he won't be
outside protesting.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton, an outspoken civil rights activist, will be the guest
of conservative commentator Armstrong Williams on Tuesday inside
the First Union Center where the convention is being held.
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton's office confirmed the visit Monday but said his entire
schedule had not been set yet. Williams said Sharpton will spend
most of the day with him, including doing his syndicated radio show
from inside the convention media area.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're just trying to show that people of different political
persuasions can try to come together and talk about their
differences,'' Williams said. ''He's a minister, and there are some
issues we have in common.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharpton is detested by many in the Republican Party, who say
he's a polarizing figure and link him to Senate candidate Hillary
Rodham Clinton. In fact, Sen. John McCain, during his bid for the
GOP presidential nomination, called Sharpton and several others
''agents of intolerance.'' Republican National Committee Chairman
Jim Nicholson called Sharpton a hatemonger, an anti-Semite and a
racist.
</P>
<P>
   In response, Sharpton filed a $30 million libel lawsuit against
the RNC and Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   What kind of reaction will Sharpton get at a GOP national
convention?
</P>
<P>
   ''It'll certainly be interesting,'' Williams laughed. ''I think
people will be shocked, but then again, he'll be with me.''
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for Sharpton's appearance, Armstrong says he'll
attend the Democratic National Convention in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're meeting each other half way, and what if it works?''
Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   This is not Sharpton's first visit to Philadelphia this year. He
attended a church rally in July to condemn the city police for the
videotaped beating of a carjacking suspect.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
