<HEADLINE> Convicted killer sentenced for stalking co-worker  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   BEDFORD, Pa. (AP) - A man whose plea agreement in a stalking
case fell apart after authorities learned he had been convicted of
stalking and killing a co-worker was sentenced to prison Monday.
</P>
<P>
   John Robert Reed, 44, of Altoona had reached a plea agreement
last spring to serve six months in jail or time served for stalking
and harassing the 22-year-old Bedford County woman when both worked
at the Seton Co. plant in Saxton last year.
</P>
<P>
   But in April, Bedford County Judge Daniel Howsare rejected that
agreement after a pre-sentence investigation revealed his
conviction in the 1995 killing. Reed then changed his plea to
innocent.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, he pleaded guilty and was sentenced to 1&AMP;frac12; to three
years in a state prison.
</P>
<P>
   At a preliminary hearing last November, the woman testified that
after the two had eaten lunch together for some time, Reed left a
teddy bear and flowers in her truck on separate occasions. She said
she was not interested in pursuing a relationship with Reed.
</P>
<P>
   But in Sept. 1999, Reed allegedly tried to get Acker to meet her
on a mountain top. He also said they need to ''look for a lost
dog'' and, on another occasion, tried to force her truck off a
rural mountain road, authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Later that month, the woman noticed something wrong with the
brakes of her truck. An inspection by a mechanic revealed they had
been cut.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Reed allegedly impersonated a private investigator
in a telephone call to Acker's home and told her that people had
been following her, including one wanted for murdering an
18-year-old female about a mile from her home.
</P>
<P>
   Later that month, as she got out of her truck at work, police
said Reed approached Acker, showed her a badge, and warned her that
people were ''making plans to rape and murder her.''
</P>
<P>
   Co-workers persuaded Acker to call police, who arrested Reed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, a New Jersey jury found Reed guilty of first-degree
murder, but in 1995 that state's Supreme Court reversed the
decision and ordered a retrial on the basis that police had
obtained an illegal confession.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors were forced to offer Reed a plea agreement to
aggravated manslaughter, which carried a 5-to-10 year prison
sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Reed spent eight years in jail before being paroled. Police said
Reed moved to Altoona and began working at Seton Co. about two
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The victim in the New Jersey case, 25-year-old Susan Green of
Franklin, resembled Acker.
</P>
</TEXT>
