<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton: GOP Drug Plan Is 'Baloney'  </HEADLINE>
By SONYA ROSS
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. (AP) -- As Republicans opened their convention on
Monday in Philadelphia, President Clinton hurled criticism at them
from the warm climes of Florida. He put down their prescription
drug plan as ''a bunch of baloney'' that would help drug companies,
not the elderly or disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton left Washington's rainy weather to enjoy some Florida
sunshine and do a little fund raising. With state insurance
commissioner and Senate candidate Bill Nelson in tow, Clinton was
attending three events here and in Palm Beach that were to raise
$1.1 million for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ''Whether he wins or not -- and I believe he will -- depends in no
small measure on what people believe the election is about,''
Clinton told a luncheon for Nelson. ''The only trouble we've got in
this election right now, anywhere in America, is the confusion that
exists about what the differences are between the candidates for
president, Senate and the two parties.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, in Palm Beach, Clinton accused Republicans are trying to
cloak a destructive agenda in ''a real pretty package ... and they
just hope nobody opens the package'' before the November elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''They think we're all wet. They think we're wrong,'' Clinton
said. ''You cannot allow your fellow Floridians to ... just
sleepwalk through this election.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton visited the David Barksdale Senior Center to highlight a
study by Families USA which said Americans 65 and older pay an
average of $1,205 a year for prescriptions, an annual price tag
that will rise to $2,810 each by 2010. ''The cost of prescription
drugs is taking too big a bite out of the fixed incomes of too many
seniors and people with disabilities,'' Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   Sylvia Kessler, 81, of Tamarac, Fla., said she spends $2,300 a
year on prescriptions for high blood pressure, high cholesterol and
a heart condition. She works at the board of elections and a local
flea market to pay for those drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Kessler's medical bills went up when she fell and
broke a bone in her nose. In a voice made nasal by the cast across
her face, Kessler said she would like to stop working, but can't.
Of the GOP plan for private coverage, ''I think it's a bunch of
baloney,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton noted that insurance companies consider private coverage
for Medicare recipients unworkable, and said the plan offered by
the House would allow drug makers to charge higher prices to
recover research costs, then sell the drugs in other countries for
a profit.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm president, I'm not supposed to say it's a bunch of baloney
like Sylvia did,'' Clinton said. ''This plan that passed with the
votes of the Republican majority is basically designed for the
pharmaceutical companies who make the drugs, not the seniors who
take them. ... And it's unbelievable to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also cited a new administration report which said that
one in eight Medicare recipients is a disabled person under age 65,
a population that is expected to increase by 38 percent over the
next decade and is less likely to have private insurance coverage.
Disabled Medicare beneficiaries, Clinton said, pay 50 percent more
for drugs than do patients with full insurance coverage.
</P>
<P>
   While in Tampa, Clinton stopped by a conference on China trade,
and paused to greet a few players from the Tampa Bay Buccaneers
football team who were practicing near the senior center.
</P>
<P>
   The president planned to linger in Florida through Tuesday
afternoon to play golf.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   The White House: www.whitehouse.gov
</P>
<P>
   Families USA site: http://www.familiesusa.org
</P>
<P>
   Medicare site: http://www.medicare.gov
</P>
</TEXT>
