<HEADLINE> Geiberger Leads Wells Fargo Golf  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWCASTLE, Wash. (AP) -- Brent Geiberger wasn't exactly a picture
of health as he teed off Monday at the Wells Fargo Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   Geiberger, 32, missed the last three tournaments, including the
British Open, with a pinched nerve in his left shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night he injured a toe and was walking with a
noticeable limp.
</P>
<P>
   None of that seemed to matter as Geiberger shot a 6-under-par 66
to take a 3-shot lead after the first round of the 36-hole event at
The Golf Club at Newcastle, an east Seattle suburb.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone should have his problems,'' joked tournament host and
Seattle native Fred Couples. ''We're all as healthy as we can be
and he's killing us.''
</P>
<P>
   John Cook, Seattle native Jeff Gove and Mike Weir all had 69s.
Jeff Sluman and Peter Jacobsen both shot 70s. Couples had a 73.
</P>
<P>
   But the day belonged to Geiberger, who said his shoulder seems
to be fully healed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I had to put twice as much effort into my swing,'' Geiberger
said. ''But I've been doing a lot of stretching. I don't have any
pain right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The toe was noticeably bothering Geiberger's walking, but not
his swing.
</P>
<P>
   He had three birdies on each side and just missed a seventh
birdie when his putt on No. 5 lipped out.
</P>
<P>
   He said the time off gave him a breather.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes you take some time off and it helps,'' he said.
''You've got nothing on your mind. You're not fighting anything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
