<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 22:15 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nurses at Robert Wood Johnson hospital approve contract, averting strike </HEADLINE>
By LINDA A. JOHNSON
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) - Registered nurses at Robert Wood Johnson
University Hospital, working without a contract for 3 1/2 weeks,
voted Monday to accept the hospital's ''final offer,'' averting a
strike set for Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The nurses, represented by Local 300 of the Pace International
Union in Mountainside, voted 418-279 to accept a three-year
contract, according to Barbara Jones, vice president of
communications at the New Brunswick hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The previous contract expired June 30, but was extended by a
week. About 950 registered nurses had been working without a
contract since July 7, and on July 20, they voted 655-6 to reject
the 452-bed hospital's previous offer.
</P>
<P>
   On July 24, the day the hospital's negotiators made their final
contract offer, the union notified hospital administrators of a
possible strike at 11 p.m. Thursday, giving the 10 days' notice
required, Jones said. She said the administration had made ''all
the necessary preparations'' in case a strike occurred but would
not elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're optimistic that there will be a positive resolution'' to
the standoff, she said Monday afternoon before voting was complete.
</P>
<P>
   Union officials did not return calls seeking comment Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Jones would not discuss any provisions of the contract, but The
Home News Tribune reported that it included a 4 percent salary hike
in each year and the same health insurance as under the previous
contract, with no increase in deductibles.
</P>
<P>
   The contract also calls for the hospital to spend $1.7 million
to address concerns about staffing levels and to establish a nurse
practice committee as part of that effort, the newspaper reported.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Wood Johnson, one of the state's premier teaching
hospitals and a major trauma center, is one of a few dozen
hospitals nationwide designated a ''Magnet Hospital'' by the
American Nurses Association for the excellence of its nursing
staff. The hospital is affiliated with the Robert Wood Johnson
Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the last strike by the hospital's nurses occurred in
1978 and lasted nearly a month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-07-31-00 2215 </TRAILER>
