<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-07-31 23:56 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Powell Chides GOP, Lauds Bush  </HEADLINE>
By RON FOURNIER
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Colin Powell, the only black to serve as
chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, chided Republicans who miss
no opportunity to ''roundly and loudly condemn affirmative
action,'' even as he praised George W. Bush on Monday for bridging
racial divides.
</P>
<P>
   In a prime-time Republican National Convention address designed
to soften the edges of the GOP image, the retired general said,
''In pursuing educational reform, as well as in all other parts of
his agenda for Texas, Governor Bush has reached out to all Texans --
white, black, Latino, Asian, Native American.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell is one of the most prominent blacks on the political
scene with an appeal that crosses racial and economic lines. The
Persian Gulf War commander refused Bush's entreaties for the vice
presidential nomination, but has suggested he would like to be
secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
   Bush hinted Powell would get a job in his administration.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope his greatest service to America might still lie
ahead,'' the Texas governor said, introducing Powell by satellite
from a campaign stop in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Standing before a GOP delegation that is 83 percent white,
Powell urged the party to follow Bush's lead and reach out to
minorities, particularly blacks, ''and not just during an election
year campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, whose abortion-rights and pro-affirmative action views
put him to the left of most delegates and in opposition to Bush,
said the Republican Party has far to go to bring minorities into
the fold.
</P>
<P>
   ''We must understand the cynicism that exists in the black
community. The kind of cynicism that is created when, for example,
some in our party miss no opportunity to roundly and loudly condemn
affirmative action that helped a few thousand black kids get an
education, but you hardly heard a whimper from them over
affirmative action for lobbyists who load our federal tax codes
with preferences for special interests,'' Powell said to polite
applause from a convention hall of delegates who overwhelmingly
oppose affirmative action.
</P>
<P>
   At the 1996 convention that nominated Bob Dole, Powell heard
scattered boos when he declared, ''I believe in a woman's right to
choose and I strongly support affirmative action.''
</P>
<P>
   He did not mention abortion Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Beside race, Powell challenged Republican doctrine on spending
and class economics.
</P>
<P>
   Urging Republicans to help the poorest Americans, he said, ''The
world is watching to see if all this power and wealth is just for
the well to do, the comfortable, the privileged.''
</P>
<P>
   And Powell, chairman of a nationwide volunteer campaign to help
children, said more money is needed to improve schools and raise
teacher salaries.
</P>
<P>
   He was most blunt about race.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issue of race still casts a shadow over our society,
despite the impressive progress we have made over the last 40 years
to overcome this legacy of our troubled past that is still with
us,'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   In praising Bush, the retired general said, ''He has been
successful in bringing more and more minorities inside the tent by
responding to their deepest needs.''
</P>
<P>
   ''He will bring to the White House that same passion for
inclusion. I know that he can help bridge our racial divides,''
Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush disagrees with Powell on abortion and affirmative action,
but that didn't seem to matter to Republicans here.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think General Powell's speech shows that Republicans are
diverse and tolerant -- not just the classic white, rich guys with
an attitude,'' said Jose Alcaraz, 43, an accountant from Miami.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Republican Party has grown up and is willing to hear
provocative messages from people it respects. And the Republican
Party respects Colin Powell,'' said Mike Huckabee, a conservative
governor from Arkansas.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats said they were unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights leader Jesse Jackson said Powell ''gave a
tremendous civil rights address about poverty, schools and drugs,
but the Bush budget of debt elimination and tax relief does not
leave the money'' to deal with those issues.
</P>
<P>
   Bush strategist Karl Rove said Powell's appearance spoke loudly
for Bush's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''The signal this sends is that Republicans want to take the
next step in improving the lives of all Americans and it shows what
the governor means by 'compassionate conservatism,''' Rove said.
''It also shows that the governor is strong enough to surround
himself by strong leaders.''
</P>
<P>
   The retired Army general told delegates that education is the
nation's highest priority.
</P>
<P>
   ''So many of our problems we worry about go back to how we raise
our children. The problem is as simple as this: We either build our
children the way we know how or we build more jails,'' Powell said.
''Time to stop building jails.''
</P>
<P>
   ''They are America's promise,'' he said of the nation's
children. ''The problem is us -- if we fail to give them what they
need to be successful in life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
